{"title_page": "Ed Sullivan Theater", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox theatre\n| name               = Ed Sullivan Theater\n| image              = Ed Sullivan Theater (48047407856).jpg\n| image_size         = \n| image_alt          = \n| caption            = The Ed Sullivan Theater with ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'' marquee\n| image_map          = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n| address            = 1697 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]]\n| city               = [[New York City]]\n| country            = [[United States]]\n| designation        = \n| coordinates        = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|region:XX_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| architect          = \n| builder            = \n| owner              = [[ViacomCBS]]\n| tenant             = [[Late Show (CBS TV series)|The Late Show]]\n| operator           = \n| capacity           = 457\n| type               = Television studio<br>(Former Broadway)\n| opened             = 1927 <!--{{Start date|YYYY|MM|FF}}-->\n| reopened           = 1993<br/>2015\n| yearsactive        = \n| rebuilt            = \n| closed             = 1992 <br/>2015 <!--{{End date|YYYY|MM|FF}}-->\n| demolished         = \n| othernames         = Hammerstein's Theatre<br>Manhattan Theatre<br>Billy Rose's Music Hall<br>CBS Radio Playhouse No. 1<br>CBS Studio 50\n| production         = ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]''<br>{{small|(1953\u20131971)}}<br>''[[The Merv Griffin Show]]''<br>{{small|(1969\u20131970)}}<br>''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]''<br>{{small|(1993\u20132015)}}<br>''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]''<br>{{small|(2015\u2013present)}}\n| currentuse         = Television studio\n| parking            = \n| publictransit      =\n| website            = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | embed = yes\n  | name = Ed Sullivan Theater\n  | nrhp_type = nrhp\n  | location = \n  | nearest_city = \n  | locmapin =United States Manhattan\n  | coordinates = {{coord|40|45|49.8|N|73|58|58|W|region:US-NY_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n  | area = \n  | architect = [[Herbert J. Krapp]]\n  | architecture = [[Neo-Gothic]]\n  | added = November 17, 1997\n  | visitation_num = \n  | visitation_year = \n  | refnum = 97001303\n  | mpsub = \n  | governing_body = [[CBS Corporation]]\n}}\n}}\n[[File:Ed Sullivan.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Ed Sullivan]]]]\n\nThe '''Ed Sullivan Theater''' is a [[theatre (structure)|theater]] located at 1697\u20131699 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]], between [[53rd Street (Manhattan)|West 53rd]] and [[54th Street (Manhattan)|West 54th]], in the [[Theater District]] in [[Manhattan]], New York City.<ref name=\"AIA\">White, Norval & Willensky, Elliot; ''AIA Guide to New York City'', 4th Edition; New York Chapter, [[American Institute of Architects]]; Crown Publishers/Random House. 2000. {{ISBN|0-8129-3106-8}}; {{ISBN|0-8129-3107-6}}. p.266.</ref> The theater has been used as a venue for live and taped [[CBS]] broadcasts since 1936.<ref>[http://www.edsullivan.com/ed-sullivan-theater The History of the Ed Sullivan Theater] at EdSullivan.com</ref>\n\nIt is historically known as the home of ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' and the site of both [[Elvis Presley]]'s second and third appearances on it (his first appearance was filmed remotely at [[CBS Studio Center]] in Hollywood{{citation needed|date=October 2019}},) as well as [[The Beatles]]' [[The Ed Sullivan Show#The_Beatles|debut performance in the United States]]. Since 1993, it has been home to CBS' late night talk show, ''[[The Late Show (franchise)|The Late Show]].'' CBS began using the theater during [[David Letterman]]'s [[Late Show with David Letterman|tenure]] as host, and [[Stephen Colbert]] retained it when he [[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert|took over the show]] in 2015. It is on the [[List of Registered Historic Places in New York County, New York|National Register of Historic Places]], and the interior has been designated a landmark by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]].\n\n==First 66 years==\nThe 13-story, brown brick and [[terra cotta]] office building<ref name=nytimes>Gray, Christopher. [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/27/realestate/27scapes.html \"Streetscapes | Ed Sullivan Theater: If the Soundproofed Walls Could Talk\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 23, 2009</ref> with a ground-floor theater was designed by architect [[Herbert J. Krapp]].<ref name=\"AIA\"/> It was built by [[Arthur Hammerstein]] between 1925 and 1927,<ref name=\"AIA\"/> and was named '''Hammerstein's Theatre''' after his father, [[Oscar Hammerstein I]]. The [[neo-Gothic]] interior contains pointed-arch stained-glass windows with scenes from the elder Hammerstein's opera productions. The first production at the theater was the three-hour musical ''Golden Dawn'', the second male lead of which was [[Cary Grant]], then still using his birth name, Archie Leach.<ref name=nytimes /> Arthur Hammerstein went [[bankrupt]] in 1931, and lost ownership of the building.<ref name=nytimes />\n\nIt later went by the name '''Manhattan Theatre''', '''[[Billy Rose]]'s Music Hall''', and the Manhattan once again.<ref name=\":0\">http://www.ibdb.com/venue.php?id=1182</ref> In the 1930s, it became a nightclub.<ref name=\":0\" /> After [[CBS]] obtained a long-term lease on the property, the radio network began broadcasting from there in 1936, moving in broadcast facilities it had leased at [[NBC Studios (New York)|NBC Studios]] in [[NBC Radio City Studios|Radio City]].<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> Architect [[William Lescaze]] renovated the interior, keeping nearly all of the Krapp design but covering many walls with smooth white panels, his work earning praise from the magazine ''Architectural Forum''.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> The debut broadcast was the ''[[Major Bowes Amateur Hour]]''.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> The theater had various names during the network's tenancy, including '''Radio Theater #3''' and the '''CBS Radio Playhouse'''.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was converted for television in 1950, when it became '''CBS-TV Studio 50'''.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the early and mid-Fifties, the theater played host to many of the live telecasts of ''[[The Jackie Gleason Show]].''\n\nNewspaper columnist and impresario [[Ed Sullivan]], who had started hosting his variety show ''Toast of the Town'', soon renamed ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'', from the [[Maxine Elliott Theatre]] (CBS Studio 51) on West 39th Street in 1948, moved to Studio 50 a few years later. The theater was officially renamed for Sullivan at the end of his \"20th Anniversary Celebration\" telecast on December 10, 1967.\n\nIn the 1960s, Studio 50 was one of CBS' busiest stages, used not only for Sullivan's program but also for ''[[The Merv Griffin Show]]'',<ref name=\"query.nytimes.com\">McFadden, Robert D. [https://www.nytimes.com/1993/02/22/arts/a-building-with-a-history-from-bootleggers-to-beatles.html \"A Building With a History, From Bootleggers to Beatles\"] ''The New York Times'', February 22, 1993]</ref> as well as several game shows. In 1965, Studio 50 was converted to color, and the first color episode of ''The Ed Sullivan Show'' debuted from the theater on October 31, 1965. (The program originated from [[CBS Television City]] in color for the previous six weeks while the color equipment was installed. One earlier color episode of the program originated from Studio 72 at Broadway and 81st on August 22, 1954.<ref>[http://www.tv.com/the-ed-sullivan-show/september-19-1965-series-now-in-color---red-skelton-dino-desi-and-billy-eddie-fisher/episode/106592/summary.html TV.com listing for September 19, 1965 episode of the Ed Sullivan Show.]</ref>) ''[[What's My Line?]],'' ''[[To Tell the Truth]]'' and ''[[Password (TV series)|Password]]'' also called the studio home after CBS began broadcasting regularly in color; previously, they had been taped around the corner at CBS-TV Studio 52, which later became the [[Nightclub|disco]] [[Studio 54]]. The first episode of regular color telecasts of ''[[What's My Line?]]'' was broadcast live on September 11, 1966.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} ''Line'' and ''Truth'' remained at Studio 50 even after they moved from CBS to first-run syndication in the late 1960s and early 1970s.\n\nThe Ed Sullivan Theater was also the first home for ''[[Pyramid (game show)|The $10,000 Pyramid]],'' with its huge end-game board set at the rear of the stage, in 1973. Other short-lived game shows produced at the Ed included ''[[Musical Chairs (1975 TV series)|Musical Chairs]]'' with singer [[Adam Wade (singer)|Adam Wade]] (1975), ''[[Shoot For The Stars]]'' with [[Geoff Edwards]] (1977) (which was an NBC show), and ''[[Pass the Buck (U.S. game show)|Pass the Buck]]'' with [[Bill Cullen]] (1978).\n\nThe CBS lease on the building expired in 1981<ref name=\"query.nytimes.com\"/> and it became a [[Reeves Entertainment]] [[Teletape Studios|teletape]] facility. As such it hosted the [[sitcom]] ''[[Kate & Allie]]'', which ran from 1984 to 1989 (as it happened, on CBS), as well as the early [[Nickelodeon]] talk show ''[[Livewire (talk show)|Livewire]]''.<ref name=livewire>Greene, Alexis. [https://www.nytimes.com/1982/04/25/arts/what-cable-offers-children.html \"What Cable Offers Children\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', April 25, 1982</ref> In 1990, [[David Niles (Director)|David Niles]]/1125 Productions signed onto the lease, with the theater to house his [[HDTV]] studio and new Broadway show ''[[Dreamtime (musical)|Dreamtime]]''. On October 17, 1992, an NBC special celebrating [[Phil Donahue]]'s 25 years on television taped in the theater. The following month, [[NBC News]] used the theater for its November 1992 election night coverage.<ref>{{cite news\n  | authorlink = Frazier Moore\n  | author = Frazier Moore\n  | title = Networks Ready the Grand Finale of Election Night '92\n  | url = http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1992/Networks-Ready-the-Grand-Finale-of-Election-92/id-0846dba3ec51d5367167bf02c26a721e\n  | publisher = Associated Press\n  | date = November 3, 1992\n  | accessdate = August 17, 2015\n}}</ref>\n\n==''Late Show with David Letterman''==\n{{main article|Late Show with David Letterman}}\n[[File:The Late Show Ed Sullivan Theater photo D Ramey Logan.jpg|thumb|left|150px|The Ed Sullivan Theater with the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' marquee]]\nWhen [[David Letterman]] switched networks from NBC to CBS, CBS bought the theater in February 1993 from Winthrop Financial Associates of Boston for $4.5 million, as the broadcast location for his new show, ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]''.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news| last=Carter | first=Bill | url= https://www.nytimes.com/1993/02/22/theater/cbs-buys-a-theater-to-keep-letterman-on-new-york-s-stage.html |title= CBS Buys a Theater To Keep Letterman On New York's Stage | publisher= The New York Times | date=February 22, 1993}}</ref> The existing tenant, Niles' ''Dreamtime'', was given four weeks to vacate. Due to the economics of moving the show and the lack of a comparable available Broadway theater, ''Dreamtime'' closed. The quick sale and vacancy of the building earned the realtor the Henry Hart Rice Achievement Award<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121020005411/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-15195811.html \"Ed Sullivan Theater Is Deal of the Year\"], ''[[Real Estate Weekly]]'', April 20, 1994</ref> for the Most Ingenious Deal of the Year for 1993.<ref>Gerard, Eric R. [http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-15414002.html?Q=sale%20ed%20sullivan%20theater%20and%20office%20building%20to%20CBS \"Deal-of-the-year: how it got done\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080602143749/http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-15414002.html?Q=sale%20ed%20sullivan%20theater%20and%20office%20building%20to%20CBS |date=June 2, 2008 }}, ''Real Estate Weekly'', May 11, 1994. Opening of article, via encyclopedia.com</ref>\n\nThe theater was reconfigured into a studio, with lighting and sound adjustments; the number of seats was reduced from 1,200 to 400. During the renovation the stained glass windows were removed and stored by [[CBS]] in an arrangement with the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]; the window openings were covered with acoustic material.<ref name=nytimes /> The architectural firm that did the work, [[James Polshek|Polshek Partnership]], notes on its web site that \"to preserve the architectural integrity of the landmark, all interventions are reversible.\"<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.polshek.com/perf_sullivan.htm | title= The Ed Sullivan Theater| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20030331210234/http://www.polshek.com/perf_sullivan.htm | archivedate= March 31, 2003 | publisher= Polshek Partnership| accessdate=February 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, it took nearly four months to retrofit the theater with the cabling and equipment necessary to broadcast [[high definition television]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\nLetterman's production company [[Worldwide Pants]] had its offices in the theater's office building from 1993 until shortly after the conclusion of Letterman hosting ''Late Show'' in 2015.<ref name=wrap>{{cite news|title=David Letterman\u2019s Final \u2018Late Show': What\u2019s Next for His Production Company Worldwide Pants|url=https://www.thewrap.com/david-letterman-final-show-worldwide-pants-what-next-cbs-rob-burnett/|accessdate=May 21, 2015|work=The Wrap|date=May 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==''The Late Show with Stephen Colbert''==\n{{main article|The Late Show with Stephen Colbert}}\nLetterman's successor, [[Stephen Colbert]], continues to broadcast ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'' from the Ed Sullivan Theater, although extensive renovations were made between the two hosts' tenures.<ref name=Colbert>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/live-new-york-it-late-show-stephen-colbert-blog-entry-1.1877332 |title=Live from New York: It's the 'Late Show' with Stephen Colbert |last=Lovett |first=Ken |date=July 23, 2014 |website=NYDailyNews.com |publisher=New York Daily News |accessdate=July 23, 2014}}</ref>  Removal of the Letterman set took place only a few hours after his last show, on May 20, 2015.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://nypost.com/2015/05/21/cbs-throws-david-letterman-set-into-dumpster/ | work=New York Post | first1=Sophia | last1=Rosenbaum | first2=Beckie | last2=Strum | title=CBS throws Letterman set into Dumpster | date=May 21, 2015}}</ref> Letterman's marquee was also removed, and was temporarily replaced by a banner promoting the Angelo's Pizza restaurant adjacent to the theater, featuring Colbert posing with a slice of pizza.<ref name=\"time-angelospizza\">{{cite news|title=Ed Sullivan Theater Marquee Gets An Unexpected Makeover|url=http://time.com/3946602/ed-sullivan-theater-marquee-gets-an-unexpected-makeover/|website=Time|accessdate=July 16, 2015|first=Jacob|last=Koffler|date=July 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe theater underwent a full restoration to its original 1927 splendor, including the exposure of the theater's [[dome]], which had been covered up by air ducts and sound buffers, the re-installation of the original stained-glass windows, which had been removed and placed in storage during the Letterman era, and the restoration of a wooden chandelier with individual stained-glass chambers that house its bulbs. The restoration was made possible due to advances in technology that allowed less sound and video equipment to cover up the auditorium's architectural details.<ref>{{cite news\n  | author = Joel Lovell\n  | title = The Late, Great Stephen Colbert\n  | url = https://www.gq.com/story/stephen-colbert-gq-cover-story\n  | work = [[GQ]]\n  | date = August 17, 2015\n  | accessdate = August 17, 2015\n  | quote = \n}}</ref> CBS executive Richard Hart explained that Colbert was initially hesitant to use the theater, but called for the restoration after he was informed about the dome while touring the facility.<ref name=\"nyt-colbertreno\"/> \n\nColbert described his new set as being \"intimate\"; it features a multi-tier design, with extensive use of LED lighting and video projection backdrops, and a larger desk area than that of Letterman.<ref name=\"nyt-colbertreno\"/> Exposed for the new show, the Sullivan's dome is lit up with a [[Video projector|digital projection]] system which is used to display images above the theater, such as a kaleidoscopic pattern featuring images of Colbert's face and the CBS logo.<ref name=\"nyt-colbertreno\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/10/arts/television/stephen-colberts-shiny-new-home-on-broadway-reflects-its-past.html|title=Stephen Colbert\u2019s Shiny New Home on Broadway Reflects Its Past|last=Koblin|first=John|date=September 9, 2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 15, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> New, larger audience seats were installed, reducing the overall capacity from 461 to 370 .<ref name=\"nyt-colbertreno\"/> The theater's new marquee was designed to have a \"glitzy\" appearance appropriate for Broadway; CBS late-night executive [[Vincent Favale]] joked that Colbert's marquee made the new rear marquee installed at [[30 Rockefeller Plaza]] for ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'' as part of the re-signage from the GE Building to the [[Comcast]] Building look like a [[mall kiosk]] in comparison.<ref name=\"nyt-colbertreno\" />\n\n== Other uses ==\nThe theatre served as a stage for ''[[The Rosie O'Donnell Show]]'' for a week of shows in October 1996 when several eighth-floor studios at NBC's [[30 Rockefeller Center]] headquarters experienced complications from an electrical fire.{{Citation needed|date=February 2014}} \n\nThe theatre has hosted most of the New York-based finales for the reality game show ''[[Survivor (U.S. TV series)|Survivor]]''. The Ed Sullivan Theater was first used for ''[[Survivor: The Amazon]]'' (as a [[contingency plan]] due to rain scrubbing plans for a live finale outdoors in [[Central Park]]) and was subsequently used for every even-numbered season from ''[[Survivor: Palau]]'' to ''[[Survivor: One World]]''.\n\nIn the 21st century, the theater has hosted roof-top or marquee-top concerts by a few musicians:\n*[[Dave Matthews Band]] on July 15, 2002\n*[[Audioslave]] on November 25, 2002 (their debut live appearance)<ref>{{cite web|title=Audioslave Make Live Debut In New York City|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|year=2002|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/audioslave-make-live-debut-in-new-york-city/|accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Phish]] on June 21, 2004<ref>{{cite web| url= http://phish.net/setlists/?d=2004-06-21 | title= June 21, 2004 Setlist | work= phish.net |quote= Notes: Phish performed on top of the theater's second-floor marquee at West 53rd Street and Broadway}}</ref>\n*[[Paul McCartney]] on July 15, 2009<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/17/business/media/17late.html | title= Helped by a Big Name, Letterman Bounces Back| publisher= The New York Times |date= July 16, 2009 | first=Bill | last=Carter}}</ref>\n*[[Eminem]] and [[Jay-Z]] in June 2010<ref>{{cite web | title= Jay-Z and Eminem Perform Surprise Rooftop Concert in NYC | url= http://923now.cbslocal.com/2010/06/21/jay-z-and-eminem-perform-surprise-rooftop-concert-in-ny/ | date= June 21, 2010 | publisher= CBS Local Media | accessdate= February 22, 2014 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140405042854/http://923now.cbslocal.com/2010/06/21/jay-z-and-eminem-perform-surprise-rooftop-concert-in-ny/ | archive-date= April 5, 2014 | url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nOn February 9, 2014, the 50th anniversary of the Beatles' first ''Ed Sullivan'' performance, [[CBS News]] hosted a roundtable discussion at the theater. [[Anthony Mason (journalist)|Anthony Mason]] moderated the panel, which consisted of [[Pattie Boyd]], [[Neil Innes]], [[Mick Jones (Foreigner)|Mick Jones]], [[Tad Kubler]], [[John Oates]], [[Andrew Oldham]], [[Nile Rodgers]] and [[Julie Taymor]]. A replica of the marquee to the theater as it looked the night of the original performance also covered up the Late Show with David Letterman marquee over the weekend.<ref>[http://newyork.cbslocal.com/category/cbs-news-50-years-later/ CBS News: 50 Years Later ] ''CBS New York''</ref> David Letterman interviewed Paul McCartney and [[Ringo Starr]] in the theater as part of a related [[Grammy]] tribute special which aired on CBS around the same time.\n\n''[[CBS This Morning]]'' temporarily relocated to the Ed Sullivan Theater on March 19, 2020, utilizing a portable desk located center stage away from Colbert's desk set and the band's setup; its normal facilities at the [[CBS Broadcast Center]] were shut down in the wake of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], after several [[CBS News]] staffers tested positive for the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|novel coronavirus]].<ref name=\"thr-cbstmatest\">{{cite news |last1=Barr |first1=Jeremy |title=CBS News to Film Morning Show From 'Late Show's' Ed Sullivan Theater |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cbs-news-film-morning-show-late-shows-ed-sullivan-theater-1285179 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=March 18, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> ''The Late Show'' was in production hiatus at the time due to the pandemic;<ref name=\"deadline-cbstmatest\">{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Ted |title=\u2018CBS This Morning\u2019 To Move To Ed Sullivan Theater As Coronavirus Precaution |url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-cbs-news-cbs-this-morning-1202886809/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |date=March 18, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> ''Late Show'' executive producer [[Chris Licht]] had earlier served the same role for ''CBS This Morning''.<ref name=\"tvnewser-cbstmatest\">{{cite news |last1=Katz |first1=A.J. |title=CBS This Morning Will Move Operations to Ed Sullivan Theater |url=https://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/cbs-this-morning-will-move-operations-to-legendary-ed-sullivan-theater/434108/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=TVNewser |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> An earlier incarnation of ''CBS This Morning'' broadcast a week of shows from the theater in May 1995, while ''Late Show'' was taping in [[London]].<ref name=\"lat-cbstmatest1995\">{{cite news |last1=Snow |first1=Shauna |title=Beatles Documentary Coming to ABC |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-05-11-ca-64755-story.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 11, 1995}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IBDB venue|1182}}\n*[http://www.edsullivan.com/ed-sullivan-theater Ed Sullivan Theater] at edsullivan.com\n*[http://www.nyc.com/arts__attractions/ed_sullivan_theater.1607/editorial_review.aspx Ed Sullivan Theater] at nyc.com\n*[http://www.newyorkcitytheatre.com/theaters/edsullivantheater/theater.php Ed Sullivan Theater] at newyorkcitytheatre.com\n\n{{Broadway theatres}}\n{{CBS}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n{{LateShowonCBS}}\n{{Broadway (Manhattan)}}\n\n[[Category:Broadway theatres]]\n[[Category:Theatres in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:CBS television studios]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Theatres on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Broadway (Manhattan)]]\n[[Category:Midtown Manhattan]]\n[[Category:1927 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[category:Late Show (CBS TV series)]]\n[[Category:New York City interior landmarks]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox theatre\n| name               = Ed Sullivan Theater\n| image              = Ed Sullivan Theater (48047407856).jpg\n| image_size         = \n| image_alt          = \n| caption            = The Ed Sullivan Theater with ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'' marquee\n| image_map          = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n| address            = 1697 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]]\n| city               = [[New York City]]\n| country            = [[United States]]\n| designation        = \n| coordinates        = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|region:XX_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| architect          = \n| builder            = \n| owner              = [[ViacomCBS]]\n| tenant             = [[Late Show (CBS TV series)|The Late Show]]\n| operator           = \n| capacity           = 457\n| type               = Television studio<br>(Former Broadway)\n| opened             = 1927 <!--{{Start date|YYYY|MM|FF}}-->\n| reopened           = 1993<br/>2015\n| yearsactive        = \n| rebuilt            = \n| closed             = 1992 <br/>2015 <!--{{End date|YYYY|MM|FF}}-->\n| demolished         = \n| othernames         = Hammerstein's Theatre<br>Manhattan Theatre<br>Billy Rose's Music Hall<br>CBS Radio Playhouse No. 1<br>CBS Studio 50\n| production         = ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]''<br>{{small|(1953\u20131971)}}<br>''[[The Merv Griffin Show]]''<br>{{small|(1969\u20131970)}}<br>''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]''<br>{{small|(1993\u20132015)}}<br>''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]''<br>{{small|(2015\u2013present)}}\n| currentuse         = Television studio\n| parking            = \n| publictransit      =\n| website            = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | embed = yes\n  | name = Ed Sullivan Theater\n  | nrhp_type = nrhp\n  | location = \n  | nearest_city = \n  | locmapin =United States Manhattan\n  | coordinates = {{coord|40|45|49.8|N|73|58|58|W|region:US-NY_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n  | area = \n  | architect = [[Herbert J. Krapp]]\n  | architecture = [[Neo-Gothic]]\n  | added = November 17, 1997\n  | visitation_num = \n  | visitation_year = \n  | refnum = 97001303\n  | mpsub = \n  | governing_body = [[CBS Corporation]]\n}}\n}}\n[[File:Ed Sullivan.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Ed Sullivan]]]]\n\nThe '''Ed Sullivan Theater''' is a [[theatre (structure)|theater]] located at 1697\u20131699 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]], between [[53rd Street (Manhattan)|West 53rd]] and [[54th Street (Manhattan)|West 54th]], in the [[Theater District]] in [[Manhattan]], New York City.<ref name=\"AIA\">White, Norval & Willensky, Elliot; ''AIA Guide to New York City'', 4th Edition; New York Chapter, [[American Institute of Architects]]; Crown Publishers/Random House. 2000. {{ISBN|0-8129-3106-8}}; {{ISBN|0-8129-3107-6}}. p.266.</ref> The theater has been used as a venue for live and taped [[CBS]] broadcasts since 1936.<ref>[http://www.edsullivan.com/ed-sullivan-theater The History of the Ed Sullivan Theater] at EdSullivan.com</ref>\n\nIt is historically known as the home of ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' and the site of both [[Elvis Presley]]'s second and third appearances on it (his first appearance was filmed remotely at [[CBS Studio Center]] in Hollywood{{citation needed|date=October 2019}},) as well as [[The Beatles]]' [[The Ed Sullivan Show#The_Beatles|debut performance in the United States]]. Since 1993, it has been home to CBS' late night talk show, ''[[The Late Show (franchise)|The Late Show]].'' CBS began using the theater during [[David Letterman]]'s [[Late Show with David Letterman|tenure]] as host, and [[Stephen Colbert]] retained it when he [[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert|took over the show]] in 2015. It is on the [[List of Registered Historic Places in New York County, New York|National Register of Historic Places]], and the interior has been designated a landmark by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]].\n\n==First 66 years==\nThe 13-story, brown brick and [[terra cotta]] office building<ref name=nytimes>Gray, Christopher. [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/27/realestate/27scapes.html \"Streetscapes | Ed Sullivan Theater: If the Soundproofed Walls Could Talk\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 23, 2009</ref> with a ground-floor theater was designed by architect [[Herbert J. Krapp]].<ref name=\"AIA\"/> It was built by [[Arthur Hammerstein]] between 1925 and 1927,<ref name=\"AIA\"/> and was named '''Hammerstein's Theatre''' after his father, [[Oscar Hammerstein I]]. The [[neo-Gothic]] interior contains pointed-arch stained-glass windows with scenes from the elder Hammerstein's opera productions. The first production at the theater was the three-hour musical ''Golden Dawn'', the second male lead of which was [[Cary Grant]], then still using his birth name, Archie Leach.<ref name=nytimes /> Arthur Hammerstein went [[bankrupt]] in 1931, and lost ownership of the building.<ref name=nytimes />\n\nIt later went by the name '''Manhattan Theatre''', '''[[Billy Rose]]'s Music Hall''', and the Manhattan once again.<ref name=\":0\">http://www.ibdb.com/venue.php?id=1182</ref> In the 1930s, it became a nightclub.<ref name=\":0\" /> After [[CBS]] obtained a long-term lease on the property, the radio network began broadcasting from there in 1936, moving in broadcast facilities it had leased at [[NBC Studios (New York)|NBC Studios]] in [[NBC Radio City Studios|Radio City]].<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> Architect [[William Lescaze]] renovated the interior, keeping nearly all of the Krapp design but covering many walls with smooth white panels, his work earning praise from the magazine ''Architectural Forum''.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> The debut broadcast was the ''[[Major Bowes Amateur Hour]]''.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> The theater had various names during the network's tenancy, including '''Radio Theater #3''' and the '''CBS Radio Playhouse'''.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was converted for television in 1950, when it became '''CBS-TV Studio 50'''.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the early and mid-Fifties, the theater played host to many of the live telecasts of ''[[The Jackie Gleason Show]].''\n\nNewspaper columnist and impresario [[Ed Sullivan]], who had started hosting his variety show ''Toast of the Town'', soon renamed ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'', from the [[Maxine Elliott Theatre]] (CBS Studio 51) on West 39th Street in 1948, moved to Studio 50 a few years later. The theater was officially renamed for Sullivan at the end of his \"20th Anniversary Celebration\" telecast on December 10, 1967.\n\nIn the 1960s, Studio 50 was one of CBS' busiest stages, used not only for Sullivan's program but also for ''[[The Merv Griffin Show]]'',<ref name=\"query.nytimes.com\">McFadden, Robert D. [https://www.nytimes.com/1993/02/22/arts/a-building-with-a-history-from-bootleggers-to-beatles.html \"A Building With a History, From Bootleggers to Beatles\"] ''The New York Times'', February 22, 1993]</ref> as well as several game shows. In 1965, Studio 50 was converted to color, and the first color episode of ''The Ed Sullivan Show'' debuted from the theater on October 31, 1965. (The program originated from [[CBS Television City]] in color for the previous six weeks while the color equipment was installed. One earlier color episode of the program originated from Studio 72 at Broadway and 81st on August 22, 1954.<ref>[http://www.tv.com/the-ed-sullivan-show/september-19-1965-series-now-in-color---red-skelton-dino-desi-and-billy-eddie-fisher/episode/106592/summary.html TV.com listing for September 19, 1965 episode of the Ed Sullivan Show.]</ref>) ''[[What's My Line?]],'' ''[[To Tell the Truth]]'' and ''[[Password (TV series)|Password]]'' also called the studio home after CBS began broadcasting regularly in color; previously, they had been taped around the corner at CBS-TV Studio 52, which later became the [[Nightclub|disco]] [[Studio 54]]. The first episode of regular color telecasts of ''[[What's My Line?]]'' was broadcast live on September 11, 1966.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} ''Line'' and ''Truth'' remained at Studio 50 even after they moved from CBS to first-run syndication in the late 1960s and early 1970s.\n\nThe Ed Sullivan Theater was also the first home for ''[[Pyramid (game show)|The $10,000 Pyramid]],'' with its huge end-game board set at the rear of the stage, in 1973. Other short-lived game shows produced at the Ed included ''[[Musical Chairs (1975 TV series)|Musical Chairs]]'' with singer [[Adam Wade (singer)|Adam Wade]] (1975), ''[[Shoot For The Stars]]'' with [[Geoff Edwards]] (1977) (which was an NBC show), and ''[[Pass the Buck (U.S. game show)|Pass the Buck]]'' with [[Bill Cullen]] (1978).\n\nThe CBS lease on the building expired in 1981<ref name=\"query.nytimes.com\"/> and it became a [[Reeves Entertainment]] [[Teletape Studios|teletape]] facility. As such it hosted the [[sitcom]] ''[[Kate & Allie]]'', which ran from 1984 to 1989 (as it happened, on CBS), as well as the early [[Nickelodeon]] talk show ''[[Livewire (talk show)|Livewire]]''.<ref name=livewire>Greene, Alexis. [https://www.nytimes.com/1982/04/25/arts/what-cable-offers-children.html \"What Cable Offers Children\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', April 25, 1982</ref> In 1990, [[David Niles (Director)|David Niles]]/1125 Productions signed onto the lease, with the theater to house his [[HDTV]] studio and new Broadway show ''[[Dreamtime (musical)|Dreamtime]]''. On October 17, 1992, an NBC special celebrating [[Phil Donahue]]'s 25 years on television taped in the theater. The following month, [[NBC News]] used the theater for its November 1992 election night coverage.<ref>{{cite news\n  | authorlink = Frazier Moore\n  | author = Frazier Moore\n  | title = Networks Ready the Grand Finale of Election Night '92\n  | url = http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1992/Networks-Ready-the-Grand-Finale-of-Election-92/id-0846dba3ec51d5367167bf02c26a721e\n  | publisher = Associated Press\n  | date = November 3, 1992\n  | accessdate = August 17, 2015\n}}</ref>\n\n==''Late Show with David Letterman''==\n{{main article|Late Show with David Letterman}}\n[[File:The Late Show Ed Sullivan Theater photo D Ramey Logan.jpg|thumb|left|150px|The Ed Sullivan Theater with the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' marquee]]\nWhen [[David Letterman]] switched networks from NBC to CBS, CBS bought the theater in February 1993 from Winthrop Financial Associates of Boston for $4.5 million, as the broadcast location for his new show, ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]''.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news| last=Carter | first=Bill | url= https://www.nytimes.com/1993/02/22/theater/cbs-buys-a-theater-to-keep-letterman-on-new-york-s-stage.html |title= CBS Buys a Theater To Keep Letterman On New York's Stage | publisher= The New York Times | date=February 22, 1993}}</ref> The existing tenant, Niles' ''Dreamtime'', was given four weeks to vacate. Due to the economics of moving the show and the lack of a comparable available Broadway theater, ''Dreamtime'' closed. The quick sale and vacancy of the building earned the realtor the Henry Hart Rice Achievement Award<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121020005411/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-15195811.html \"Ed Sullivan Theater Is Deal of the Year\"], ''[[Real Estate Weekly]]'', April 20, 1994</ref> for the Most Ingenious Deal of the Year for 1993.<ref>Gerard, Eric R. [http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-15414002.html?Q=sale%20ed%20sullivan%20theater%20and%20office%20building%20to%20CBS \"Deal-of-the-year: how it got done\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080602143749/http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-15414002.html?Q=sale%20ed%20sullivan%20theater%20and%20office%20building%20to%20CBS |date=June 2, 2008 }}, ''Real Estate Weekly'', May 11, 1994. Opening of article, via encyclopedia.com</ref>\n\nThe theater was reconfigured into a studio, with lighting and sound adjustments; the number of seats was reduced from 1,200 to 400. During the renovation the stained glass windows were removed and stored by [[CBS]] in an arrangement with the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]; the window openings were covered with acoustic material.<ref name=nytimes /> The architectural firm that did the work, [[James Polshek|Polshek Partnership]], notes on its web site that \"to preserve the architectural integrity of the landmark, all interventions are reversible.\"<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.polshek.com/perf_sullivan.htm | title= The Ed Sullivan Theater| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20030331210234/http://www.polshek.com/perf_sullivan.htm | archivedate= March 31, 2003 | publisher= Polshek Partnership| accessdate=February 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, it took nearly four months to retrofit the theater with the cabling and equipment necessary to broadcast [[high definition television]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\nLetterman's production company [[Worldwide Pants]] had its offices in the theater's office building from 1993 until shortly after the conclusion of Letterman hosting ''Late Show'' in 2015.<ref name=wrap>{{cite news|title=David Letterman\u2019s Final \u2018Late Show': What\u2019s Next for His Production Company Worldwide Pants|url=https://www.thewrap.com/david-letterman-final-show-worldwide-pants-what-next-cbs-rob-burnett/|accessdate=May 21, 2015|work=The Wrap|date=May 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==''The Late Show with Stephen Colbert''==\n{{main article|The Late Show with Stephen Colbert}}\nLetterman's successor, [[Stephen Colbert]], continues to broadcast ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'' from the Ed Sullivan Theater, although extensive renovations were made between the two hosts' tenures.<ref name=Colbert>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/live-new-york-it-late-show-stephen-colbert-blog-entry-1.1877332 |title=Live from New York: It's the 'Late Show' with Stephen Colbert |last=Lovett |first=Ken |date=July 23, 2014 |website=NYDailyNews.com |publisher=New York Daily News |accessdate=July 23, 2014}}</ref>  Removal of the Letterman set took place only a few hours after his last show, on May 20, 2015.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://nypost.com/2015/05/21/cbs-throws-david-letterman-set-into-dumpster/ | work=New York Post | first1=Sophia | last1=Rosenbaum | first2=Beckie | last2=Strum | title=CBS throws Letterman set into Dumpster | date=May 21, 2015}}</ref> Letterman's marquee was also removed, and was temporarily replaced by a banner promoting the Angelo's Pizza restaurant adjacent to the theater, featuring Colbert posing with a slice of pizza.<ref name=\"time-angelospizza\">{{cite news|title=Ed Sullivan Theater Marquee Gets An Unexpected Makeover|url=http://time.com/3946602/ed-sullivan-theater-marquee-gets-an-unexpected-makeover/|website=Time|accessdate=July 16, 2015|first=Jacob|last=Koffler|date=July 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe theater underwent a full restoration to its original 1927 splendor, including the exposure of the theater's [[dome]], which had been covered up by air ducts and sound buffers, the re-installation of the original stained-glass windows, which had been removed and placed in storage during the Letterman era, and the restoration of a wooden chandelier with individual stained-glass chambers that house its bulbs. The restoration was made possible due to advances in technology that allowed less sound and video equipment to cover up the auditorium's architectural details.<ref>{{cite news\n  | author = Joel Lovell\n  | title = The Late, Great Stephen Colbert\n  | url = https://www.gq.com/story/stephen-colbert-gq-cover-story\n  | work = [[GQ]]\n  | date = August 17, 2015\n  | accessdate = August 17, 2015\n  | quote = \n}}</ref> CBS executive Richard Hart explained that Colbert was initially hesitant to use the theater, but called for the restoration after he was informed about the dome while touring the facility.<ref name=\"nyt-colbertreno\"/> \n\nColbert described his new set as being \"intimate\"; it features a multi-tier design, with extensive use of LED lighting and video projection backdrops, and a larger desk area than that of Letterman.<ref name=\"nyt-colbertreno\"/> Exposed for the new show, the Sullivan's dome is lit up with a [[Video projector|digital projection]] system which is used to display images above the theater, such as a kaleidoscopic pattern featuring images of Colbert's face and the CBS logo.<ref name=\"nyt-colbertreno\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/10/arts/television/stephen-colberts-shiny-new-home-on-broadway-reflects-its-past.html|title=Stephen Colbert\u2019s Shiny New Home on Broadway Reflects Its Past|last=Koblin|first=John|date=September 9, 2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 15, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> New, larger audience seats were installed, reducing the overall capacity from 461 to 370 .<ref name=\"nyt-colbertreno\"/> The theater's new marquee was designed to have a \"glitzy\" appearance appropriate for Broadway; CBS late-night executive [[Vincent Favale]] joked that Colbert's marquee made the new rear marquee installed at [[30 Rockefeller Plaza]] for ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'' as part of the re-signage from the GE Building to the [[Comcast]] Building look like a [[mall kiosk]] in comparison.<ref name=\"nyt-colbertreno\" />\n\n== Other uses ==\nThe theatre served as a stage for ''[[The Rosie O'Donnell Show]]'' for a week of shows in October 1996 when several eighth-floor studios at NBC's [[30 Rockefeller Center]] headquarters experienced complications from an electrical fire.{{Citation needed|date=February 2014}} \n\nThe theatre has hosted most of the New York-based finales for the reality game show ''[[Survivor (U.S. TV series)|Survivor]]''. The Ed Sullivan Theater was first used for ''[[Survivor: The Amazon]]'' (as a [[contingency plan]] due to rain scrubbing plans for a live finale outdoors in [[Central Park]]) and was subsequently used for every even-numbered season from ''[[Survivor: Palau]]'' to ''[[Survivor: One World]]''.\n\nIn the 21st century, the theater has hosted roof-top or marquee-top concerts by a few musicians:\n*[[Dave Matthews Band]] on July 15, 2002\n*[[Audioslave]] on November 25, 2002 (their debut live appearance)<ref>{{cite web|title=Audioslave Make Live Debut In New York City|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|year=2002|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/audioslave-make-live-debut-in-new-york-city/|accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Phish]] on June 21, 2004<ref>{{cite web| url= http://phish.net/setlists/?d=2004-06-21 | title= June 21, 2004 Setlist | work= phish.net |quote= Notes: Phish performed on top of the theater's second-floor marquee at West 53rd Street and Broadway}}</ref>\n*[[Paul McCartney]] on July 15, 2009<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/17/business/media/17late.html | title= Helped by a Big Name, Letterman Bounces Back| publisher= The New York Times |date= July 16, 2009 | first=Bill | last=Carter}}</ref>\n*[[Eminem]] and [[Jay-Z]] in June 2010<ref>{{cite web | title= Jay-Z and Eminem Perform Surprise Rooftop Concert in NYC | url= http://923now.cbslocal.com/2010/06/21/jay-z-and-eminem-perform-surprise-rooftop-concert-in-ny/ | date= June 21, 2010 | publisher= CBS Local Media | accessdate= February 22, 2014 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140405042854/http://923now.cbslocal.com/2010/06/21/jay-z-and-eminem-perform-surprise-rooftop-concert-in-ny/ | archive-date= April 5, 2014 | url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nOn February 9, 2014, the 50th anniversary of the Beatles' first ''Ed Sullivan'' performance, [[CBS News]] hosted a roundtable discussion at the theater. [[Anthony Mason (journalist)|Anthony Mason]] moderated the panel, which consisted of [[Pattie Boyd]], [[Neil Innes]], [[Mick Jones (Foreigner)|Mick Jones]], [[Tad Kubler]], [[John Oates]], [[Andrew Oldham]], [[Nile Rodgers]] and [[Julie Taymor]]. A replica of the marquee to the theater as it looked the night of the original performance also covered up the Late Show with David Letterman marquee over the weekend.<ref>[http://newyork.cbslocal.com/category/cbs-news-50-years-later/ CBS News: 50 Years Later ] ''CBS New York''</ref> David Letterman interviewed Paul McCartney and [[Ringo Starr]] in the theater as part of a related [[Grammy]] tribute special which aired on CBS around the same time.\n\n''[[CBS This Morning]]'' temporarily relocated to the Ed Sullivan Theater on March 19, 2020; its normal facilities at the [[CBS Broadcast Center]] were shut down in the wake of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], after several [[CBS News]] staffers tested positive for the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|novel coronavirus]].<ref name=\"thr-cbstmatest\">{{cite news |last1=Barr |first1=Jeremy |title=CBS News to Film Morning Show From 'Late Show's' Ed Sullivan Theater |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cbs-news-film-morning-show-late-shows-ed-sullivan-theater-1285179 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=March 18, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> ''The Late Show'' was in production hiatus at the time due to the pandemic;<ref name=\"deadline-cbstmatest\">{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Ted |title=\u2018CBS This Morning\u2019 To Move To Ed Sullivan Theater As Coronavirus Precaution |url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-cbs-news-cbs-this-morning-1202886809/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |date=March 18, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> ''Late Show'' executive producer [[Chris Licht]] had earlier served the same role for ''CBS This Morning''.<ref name=\"tvnewser-cbstmatest\">{{cite news |last1=Katz |first1=A.J. |title=CBS This Morning Will Move Operations to Ed Sullivan Theater |url=https://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/cbs-this-morning-will-move-operations-to-legendary-ed-sullivan-theater/434108/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=TVNewser |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> An earlier incarnation of ''CBS This Morning'' broadcast a week of shows from the theater in May 1995, while ''Late Show'' was taping in [[London]].<ref name=\"lat-cbstmatest1995\">{{cite news |last1=Snow |first1=Shauna |title=Beatles Documentary Coming to ABC |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-05-11-ca-64755-story.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 11, 1995}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IBDB venue|1182}}\n*[http://www.edsullivan.com/ed-sullivan-theater Ed Sullivan Theater] at edsullivan.com\n*[http://www.nyc.com/arts__attractions/ed_sullivan_theater.1607/editorial_review.aspx Ed Sullivan Theater] at nyc.com\n*[http://www.newyorkcitytheatre.com/theaters/edsullivantheater/theater.php Ed Sullivan Theater] at newyorkcitytheatre.com\n\n{{Broadway theatres}}\n{{CBS}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n{{LateShowonCBS}}\n{{Broadway (Manhattan)}}\n\n[[Category:Broadway theatres]]\n[[Category:Theatres in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:CBS television studios]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Theatres on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Broadway (Manhattan)]]\n[[Category:Midtown Manhattan]]\n[[Category:1927 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[category:Late Show (CBS TV series)]]\n[[Category:New York City interior landmarks]]\n", "name_user": "Mrschimpf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther uses", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ed_Sullivan_Theater"}
{"title_page": "Chris Hedges", "text_new": "{{use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Chris Hedges\n|image         = Chris hedges blur.jpg\n|image_size    =\n|caption       = Hedges, {{abbr|c.|circa}} 2007\n|birth_name    = Christopher Lynn Hedges\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1956|9|18}}\n|birth_place   = [[St. Johnsbury, Vermont|St. Johnsbury]], [[Vermont]], U.S.\n|death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|death_place   =\n|residence     = [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]], [[New Jersey]], U.S.\n|citizenship   = [[United States]]\n|ethnicity     =\n|education     = [[Colgate University]] <small>([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])</small><br />[[Harvard Divinity School]] <small>([[Master of Divinity|M.Div]])</small>\n|occupation    = Journalist, writer, activist, clergyman\n|employer      =\n|known_for     =\n|spouse        =\n}}\n'''Christopher Lynn Hedges''' (born September 18, 1956) is an American journalist, [[Presbyterian Church|Presbyterian]] minister, and visiting [[Princeton University]] lecturer. His books include ''[[War Is a Force That Gives Us Meaning]]'' (2002), a finalist for the [[National Book Critics Circle Award for Nonfiction]]; ''Empire of Illusion: The End of Literacy and the Triumph of Spectacle'' (2009); ''[[Death of the Liberal Class]]'' (2010); ''[[Days of Destruction, Days of Revolt]]'' (2012), written with cartoonist [[Joe Sacco]], which was a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' best-seller; ''Wages of Rebellion: The Moral Imperative of Revolt'' (2015); and his most recent ''America:  The Farewell Tour'' (2018).\n\nHedges was a columnist for the progressive news and commentary website [[Truthdig]].<ref>[http://www.truthdig.com/about Truthdig: About Us]</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=August 19, 2011 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/19/idUS428147016120110819 |title=Reuters Ex-LA Times Writer Mark Heisler Vents Again About Tribune |work=Reuters |accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2020/03/27/statement-from-striking-truthdig-workers/|title=Statement From Striking Truthdig Workers|date=2020-03-27|website=CounterPunch.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> He hosts the program ''On Contact'' for the [[RT (TV network)|RT]] (formerly Russia Today) television network.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ryan|first=Danielle|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/rt-america-was-not-pro-trump/|title=RT America Was Not 'Pro-Trump'|work=The Nation|date=January 10, 2017|access-date=August 4, 2019}}</ref> Hedges spent nearly two decades as a foreign correspondent in [[Central America]], [[Western Asia|West Asia]], [[Africa]], the Middle East, and the [[Balkans]]. He has reported from more than fifty countries, and has worked for ''[[The Christian Science Monitor]]'', [[NPR]], ''[[Dallas Morning News]]'', and ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref name=\"Simon\">{{cite web |url=http://authors.simonandschuster.com/Chris-Hedges/21025518|title=Simon & Schuster, \"Authors: Chris Hedges\"|work=Simon & Schuster|accessdate=November 27, 2014}}</ref> where he was a foreign correspondent for fifteen years (1990\u20132005).\n\nIn 2001, Hedges contributed to ''The New York Times'' staff entry that received the 2002 [[Pulitzer Prize for Explanatory Reporting]] for the paper's coverage of global terrorism. He also received the [[Amnesty International]] Global Award for Human Rights Journalism in 2002.<ref name=\"Chrisbiotruthdig\">{{cite web |title = Chris Hedges, Columnist |publisher = Truthdig |url = https://www.truthdig.com/staff/chris_hedges#bio |accessdate = 2013-09-28 }}</ref> He has taught at [[Columbia University]], [[New York University]], the [[University of Toronto]] and [[Princeton University]], where he is a visiting lecturer in [[African American studies]].<ref name=\"Simon\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Visiting Journalism Professors Roster 1964\u20132015|url=http://humanities.princeton.edu/journalism/professors/past|accessdate=28 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531003156/http://humanities.princeton.edu/journalism/professors/past|archivedate=May 31, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Anshutz Distinguished Fellowship in American Studies |url=https://www.princeton.edu/ams/anschutz/ |accessdate=28 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425054658/http://www.princeton.edu/ams/anschutz/ |archivedate=April 25, 2016 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=In Conversation with Brian Steward: Pulitzer-Prize Winning Journalist Christopher Hedges|url=http://munkschool.utoronto.ca/csus/event/9717/print/|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHedges has taught college credit courses for several years in New Jersey prisons. He teaches a course through Princeton University in which the class is composed of half prisoners and half Princeton undergraduates.<ref name=\"Chrisbiotruthdig\"/> He has described himself as a [[socialist]]<ref name=socialist>{{cite web |last=Hedges|first=Chris |url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/20081229_why_i_am_a_socialist/|title=Why I Am a Socialist|publisher=Truthdig|date=December 29, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Hedges |first=Chris |date=August 21, 2018 |title=America: The Farewell Tour |url= |location= |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |page=303 |isbn=978-0-73527-596-6 |author-link= }}</ref> and more specifically as a [[Christian anarchism|Christian anarchist]],<ref>Chris Hedges Interviewed at NYSEC [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tZSjKVijpjE&t=57m3s Youtube] Assessed 12/15/2016</ref><ref>Chris Hedges on What it Takes to be a Rebel in Modern Times [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BUgaqJZLwOg&t=16m21s Youtube] Assessed 12/15/2016</ref> identifying with Catholic activist [[Dorothy Day]] in particular.<ref>Occupy Tactics \u2013 Violence and Legitimacy in the Occupy Movement and Beyond [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F_cyzgYLaK4&t=1h15m31s Youtube] Assessed 12/15/2016</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nChristopher Lynn Hedges was born in [[St. Johnsbury, Vermont]], the son of Thelma Louise (''n\u00e9e'' Prince) and the Rev. Thomas Havard Hedges, a [[Presbyterian]] minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princetonmagazine.com/wordpress/?p=1749 |title=Chris Hedges The News Is Not Good |author=Ellen Gilbert |publisher=Princeton Magazine |date=February 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423211814/http://www.princetonmagazine.com/wordpress/?p=1749 |archivedate=April 23, 2014 }}</ref><ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:KFBV-4CZ Chris Hedges in FamilySearch]</ref> He grew up in rural [[Schoharie County, New York]], southwest of Albany. He graduated in 1975 from the [[Loomis Chaffee School]], a private [[boarding school]] in [[Windsor, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.collegequarterly.ca/2012-vol15-num01-winter/doughty.html | title =I Don't Believe in Atheists | author =Chris Hedges |author2=Howard A. Doughty | publisher =collegequarterly.ca | year =2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.loomischaffee.org/page.cfm?p=3613 | title =Notable Alumni Humanitarianism and Public Service | publisher =loomischaffee.org | date =May 15, 2013}}</ref> He founded an underground newspaper at the school that was banned by the administration and resulted in his being put on probation.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.courant.com/2003-02-21/news/0302210468_1_chris-hedges-iraq-poison | title =Writer Shares War Stories | author =Johnny Mason | newspaper=Hartford Courant |accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHedges received his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in English from [[Colgate University]] in 1979. He received a [[Master of Divinity]] degree from [[Harvard Divinity School]] (where he studied under [[James Luther Adams]]) in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/week622/hedges.html |title=Interview: Chris Hedges |publisher=PBS |date=January 31, 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310151925/http://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/week622/hedges.html |archivedate=March 10, 2013 }}</ref> He studied [[Latin]] and [[Classical Greek]] at Harvard and speaks [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[French language|French]], and [[Spanish language|Spanish]] in addition to [[English language|English]].<ref name=\"Chrisbiotruthdig\"/>\n\n==''The New York Times''== \nHedges worked for 15 years as a foreign correspondent for ''[[The New York Times]]''. He was based in the Middle East for five years, serving for four of those years as the Middle East bureau chief. He covered the war in the former Yugoslavia as the Balkan bureau chief based in Sarajevo. He later covered [[Al Qaeda]] in Europe and the Middle East from Paris.\n\nThree of Hedges' articles were based upon the stories of Iraqi defectors, who had been furnished to Hedges by the Information Collection Program of the U.S.-funded [[Iraqi National Congress]].<ref>[http://www.commondreams.org/headlines04/0316-02.htm Jonathan S. Landay and Tish Wells, \"Global Misinformation Campaign was Used to Build Case for War\" ''Knight-Ridder'', March 16, 2004] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131117010917/http://www.commondreams.org/headlines04/0316-02.htm |date=November 17, 2013 }}</ref> The program promoted stories to major media outlets in order to orchestrate U.S. intervention in Iraq in the aftermath of the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 attacks]]. Most significant of his reports in this period was a November 8, 2001, front-page story about two former [[Saddam Hussein and al-Qaeda link allegations|Iraqi military commanders who claimed to have trained foreign mujahedeen]] how to hijack planes without using guns.<ref name='alternet'>{{cite news | url = http://www.alternet.org/story/19210/ahmed_chalabi's_list_of_suckers | first = Douglas | last = McCollam | title = Ahmed Chalabi's List of Suckers: Judith Miller is only one of the many reporters from almost every blue-blooded news outfit in America who were played by the Iraqi exile | date = July 12, 2004| work = [[Alternet]] | accessdate = 2013-11-22 | quote = Chris Hedges of ''The New York Times'' wrote a page-one piece headlined \"Defectors Cite Iraqi Training for Terrorism\".}}</ref> Hedges quoted a man whom he believed to be an Iraqi general: \"These Islamic radicals ... came from a variety of countries, including Saudi Arabia, Yemen, Algeria, Egypt, and Morocco. We were training these people to attack installations important to the United States\". The two defectors also asserted there was a secret compound in [[Salman Pak facility]] where a German scientist was producing biological weapons.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/08/international/middleeast/08IRAQ.html%20| first = Chris | last = Hedges | title = Defectors Cite Iraqi Training for Terrorism | date = November 8, 2001 | work = [[The New York Times]] | accessdate = 2013-11-17}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Jack Fairweather (writer)|Jack Fairweather]] in ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'': \"The impact of the article ... was immediate: Op-eds ran in major papers, and the story was taken to a wider audience through cable-TV talk shows.<ref name='heroes in error'>{{cite news| last = Fairweather | first = Jack| authorlink = Jack Fairweather (writer) | title = Heroes in Error | date = March\u2013April 2006 | url = https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2006/03/heroes-error | work = [[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]| accessdate = November 17, 2013 | quote = How a fake general, a pliant media, and a master manipulator helped lead the United States into war.}}</ref> When [[Condoleezza Rice]], then President [[George W. Bush]]'s national security adviser, was asked about the report at a press briefing, she said, 'I think it surprises no one that Saddam Hussein is engaged in all kinds of activities that are destabilizing.{{'\"}} As late as 2006, according to Fairweather in the same article, conservative magazines including ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'' and ''[[National Review]]'' continued to use this article to justify the invasion of Iraq.<ref name='heroes in error' />\n\nIt later was revealed that the story which Hedges reported was \"an elaborate scam\". The defector whom Hedges quoted, who had identified himself as Lt. General Jamal al-Ghurairy, was a former sergeant. The real Ghurairy had never left Iraq. Hedges said that he had taken on reporting this account at the request of [[Lowell Bergman]] of ''[[Frontline (U.S. TV program)|Frontline]]'', who wanted the defectors for his show but could not go to Beirut for the interview. The trip had been organized by [[Ahmed Chalabi]], whom Hedges considered to be unreliable. Hedges said he had done the piece as a favor to Bergman, explaining, \"There has to be a level of trust between reporters. We cover each other's sources when it's a good story because otherwise everyone would get hold of it.\" Hedges had relied on the U.S. embassy in Turkey for further confirmation of the man's identity.<ref name=\"heroes in error\"/>\n\nHedges wrote two more articles that year that were informed by Chalabi-coached defectors. The second one, claiming that Iraq still held 80 Kuwaitis captured in the 1991 Gulf War in a secret underground prison, was also found to be baseless.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commondreams.org/headlines04/0316-02.htm |author1=Jonathan S. Landay |author2=Tish Wells |work=[[Knight-Ridder]] |date=March 16, 2004 |title=Iraqi Exile Group Fed False Information to News Media \u2013 Global Misinformation Campaign was Used to Build Case for War |accessdate=December 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131117010917/http://www.commondreams.org/headlines04/0316-02.htm |archivedate=November 17, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Political views and activism==\n{{quote box|width=23em|The Democratic Party is as much to blame for Trump as the Republicans. It is a full partner in the perpetuation of our political system of legalized bribery, along with the deindustrialization of the country, austerity programs, social inequality, mass incarceration and the assault on basic civil liberties. It deregulates Wall Street. It prosecutes the endless and futile wars that are draining the federal budget. We must mount independent political movements and form our own parties to sweep the Democratic and Republican elites aside or be complicit in cementing into place a corporate tyranny. Sanders won\u2019t help us. He has made that clear. We must do it without him.|salign=right|source=\u2014Chris Hedges on the Democratic Party<ref name=hedges>{{cite web|last1=Hedges|first1=Chris|title=Capitalism|url=https://www.truthdig.com/articles/et-tu-bernie-3/|website=truthdig.com|accessdate=17 June 2018|archive-url=|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>}}\nHedges was an early critic of the [[Iraq War]]. In May 2003, he delivered a commencement address at [[Rockford University|Rockford College]] in Rockford, Illinois, saying: \"We are embarking on an occupation that, if history is any guide, will be as damaging to our souls as it will be to our prestige and power and security.\"<ref>{{YouTube|SAWMgYyAtHU|Footage of the speech}}; Rockford College, May 2003</ref> His speech was received with boos and his microphone was shut off three minutes after he began speaking.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.democracynow.org/2003/5/21/new_york_times_reporter_chris_hedges|title=New York Times Reporter, Chris Hedges was Booed off the Stage and had his Microphone Cut Twice as he Delivered a Graduation Speech on War and Empire at Rockford College in Illinois |publisher=[[Democracy Now!]] |date=May 21, 2014 |accessdate=November 24, 2014}}</ref>\n{{American socialism |People}}\n''The New York Times,'' his employer, criticized his statements and issued him a formal reprimand for \"public remarks that could undermine public trust in the paper's impartiality\".<ref name=\"dallas\">Hedges, Chris; [http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/religion/stories/DN-main_17rel.ART.State.Edition1.21b687c.html A Father's Gift], ''[[Dallas Morning News]]'', 17 June 2006, accessed December 21, 2010 {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Shortly after the incident, Hedges left ''The New York Times'' to become a senior fellow at [[The Nation Institute]], and a columnist at [[Truthdig]], in addition to writing books and teaching inmates at a New Jersey correctional institution.<ref name=\"dallas\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nationinstitute.org/fellows/1328/chris_hedges |title=The Nation Institute |access-date=April 1, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150601032127/http://www.nationinstitute.org/fellows/1328/chris_hedges/ |archive-date=June 1, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHedges has worked for a decade teaching in prisons in New Jersey, and he has become a fierce critic of [[Incarceration in the United States|mass incarceration in the United States]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Marshall \"Eddie\" Conway |author2=Chris Hedges |url=http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=74&jumival=12928 |title=How Prisons Rip Off and Exploit the Incarcerated (1/2) |publisher=The Real News |date=January 4, 2015 |accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>Chris Hedges (December 29, 2014). [http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/the_prison_state_of_america_20141228 The Prison State of America]. Truthdig. Retrieved January 6, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn the 2008 United States presidential campaign, Hedges was a speech writer for candidate [[Ralph Nader]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://progressive.org/chris_hedges_interview.html |author=David Barsamian |title=An Interview with Chris Hedges |date=August 2011 |work=The Progressive |accessdate=November 27, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141204135757/http://www.progressive.org/chris_hedges_interview.html |archivedate=December 4, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2008, Hedges published a book titled ''I Don't Believe in Atheists'', in which he expresses his belief that new atheism presents a danger that is similar to religious extremism.<ref>{{Cite book|title=I Don't Believe in Atheists|last=Hedges|first=Chris|publisher=Free Press|year=2008|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn his December 29, 2008, column for Truthdig, Hedges stated that \"[t]he inability to articulate a viable socialism has been our gravest mistake. It will ensure, if this does not soon change, a ruthless [[Inverted totalitarianism|totalitarian capitalism]]\".<ref name=socialist/> He elaborated upon this in a 2013 interview with The Real News, claiming that, \"the left has been destroyed, especially the [[Far-left politics|radical left]], quite consciously in the whole name of [[Anti-communism#United States|anti-communism]]\", and:\n{{quote|[W]e have allowed ourselves to embrace an ideology which, at its core, states that all governance is about maximizing corporate profit at the expense of the citizenry. For what do we have structures of government, for what do we have institutions of state, if not to hold up all the citizenry, and especially the most vulnerable?<ref>[http://www.truthdig.com/avbooth/item/chris_hedges_the_left_has_been_destroyed_20130722/?ln Chris Hedges: 'The Left Has Been Destroyed']. Truthdig, July 22, 2013.</ref>}}\n\nIn a March 2009 column, Hedges warned that [[Human overpopulation|human over-population]] and [[Holocene extinction|mass species extinction]] are serious problems, and that any measures to save the ecosystem will be futile unless we cut population growth, and noted that, \"As long as the Earth is viewed as the personal property of the human race, a belief embraced by everyone from born-again Christians to Marxists to free-market economists, we are destined to soon inhabit a biological wasteland.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.truthdig.com/articles/we-are-breeding-ourselves-to-extinction/|title=We Are Breeding Ourselves to Extinction|last=Hedges |first=Chris |date=March 9, 2009|website= Truthdig|publisher= |access-date= January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 8, 2009, Hedges identified as a \"radical Keynesian\" during his lecture at [[The New School]], entitled \"Empire of Illusion\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_EpeF1fcji0|title=Chris Hedges' Empire of Illusion {{!}} The New School|last=Hedges|first=Chris|date=December 16, 2009|website=[[YouTube]]|publisher=[[The New School]]|access-date=August 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2010, he was arrested outside the White House along with [[Daniel Ellsberg]] and more than 100 activists who were protesting the war in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.truthdig.com/avbooth/item/hope_is_action_hedges_ellsberg_arrested_at_white_house_protest_20101217 |title='Hope Is Action': Hedges and Ellsberg Arrested at White House Protest|publisher=Truthdig|date=2010-12-17|accessdate=2014-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rawstory.com/rs/2010/12/untitled-chris-hedges-interview/ | title=Exclusive: US empire could collapse at any time, Pulitzer winner tells Raw Story |website=[[The Raw Story]]|date=December 17, 2010|accessdate=2014-11-24}}</ref>\n\nHedges appeared as a guest on an October 2011 episode of the [[CBC News Network]]'s ''[[Lang and O'Leary Exchange]]'' to discuss his support for the [[Occupy Wall Street]] protests; co-host [[Kevin O'Leary]] criticized him, saying that he sounded \"like a left-wing nutbar\". Hedges said \"it will be the last time\" he appears on the show, and compared the CBC to [[Fox News]].<ref>James Crugnale (October 12, 2011). [http://www.mediaite.com/tv/journalist-chris-hedges-argues-with-cbcs-kevin-oleary-this-sounds-like-fox-news-and-i-don%E2%80%99t-go-on-fox-news/ Journalist Chris Hedges Argues With CBC's Kevin O'Leary: 'This Sounds Like Fox News And I Don't Go On Fox News!'], ''[[Mediaite]].'' Retrieved January 24, 2014.</ref> CBC's ombudsman found O'Leary's heated remarks to be a violation of the public broadcaster's journalistic standards.<ref>{{cite news |author=Cassandra Szklarski |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2011/10/14/oleary-nutbar-ombudsman_n_1011373.html |title=Kevin O'Leary 'Nutbar' Remark Violated Journalistic Standards: CBC Ombudsman]. |work=The Huffington Post Canada |date=October 14, 2011 |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2011, Hedges was arrested with others in New York as part of the [[Occupy Wall Street]] demonstration, during which the activists staged a \"people's hearing\"<ref>[http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/chris_hedges_arrested_in_front_of_goldman_sachs_20111103/ Chris Hedges Arrested in Front of Goldman Sachs]. Truthdig. November 3, 2011.</ref> on the activities of the investment bank [[Goldman Sachs]] and blocked the entrance to their corporate headquarters.<ref>{{cite news |author=Rich Schapiro |author2=Helen Kennedy |date=November 3, 2011 |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/a-dozen-occupy-wall-street-protesters-arrested-goldman-sachs-article-1.971807 |title=More than a dozen Occupy Wall Street protesters arrested outside Goldman Sachs, Reporter/Activist Chris Hedges among those charged] |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |location=New York |accessdate=2011-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|w9qPGzqpuYc|RTAmerica}}</ref> Hedges has appeared on the syndicated ''[[Democracy Now!]]'' television program; on ''[[Breaking the Set]]'' on [[RT (TV network)|RT]] (formerly known as Russia Today), and on CBC's ''[[George Stroumboulopoulos Tonight]]''.<ref>[http://www.democracynow.org/appearances/chris_hedges Shows featuring Chris Hedges]. ''[[Democracy Now!]]'' Retrieved January 30, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://rt.com/shows/breaking-set-summary/fight-keystone-socialism-us-960/ |title=Socialist in Seattle: Kshama Sawant's revolution, the indigenous fight against Keystone XL |publisher=[[RT (TV network)|RT]] |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"strombo\">{{cite news\n|url         = http://www.cbc.ca/strombo/guest-page/chris-hedges-1.html\n|year        = 2010\n|title       = Strombo, Chris Hedges, CBC Television\n|publisher   = [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]\n|accessdate  = 2010-11-08 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, Hedges publicly supported [[Jill Stein]], the candidate of the [[Green Party of the United States]], in the [[2012 United States presidential election]].<ref name=\"Why I'm Voting Green\">{{cite web |last=Hedges|first=Chris|title=Why I'm Voting Green |url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/why_im_voting_green_20121029/|publisher=Truthdig|accessdate=April 7, 2013}}</ref> On April 7, 2013, Hedges delivered the keynote address at the [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]] of [[New Jersey]] state convention.<ref name=\"Green Party to livestream Chris Hedges keynote at NJ GP annual meeting, Sun. 4/9\">{{cite web |title=Green Party to livestream Chris Hedges keynote at NJ GP annual meeting, Sun. 4/9|url=http://www.greenpartywatch.org/2013/04/04/green-party-to-livestream-chris-hedges-keynote-at-nj-gp-annual-meeting-sun-49/|publisher=greenpartywatch.org|accessdate=April 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|C8H0ty327o0|Chris Hedges Strategy for Radical Change at Green Party of New Jersey Convention}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, Hedges and numerous celebrities appeared in a video showing support for [[Chelsea Manning]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/06/celebrity-bradley-manning-video-93041.html#ixzz2WgfpNmys |title=Celeb video: 'I am Bradley Manning' \u2013 Patrick Gavin |publisher=Politico |date=2013-06-20 |accessdate=2014-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|id=UFFkcCh-pCc|title=I am Bradley Manning (full HD)}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20, 2014, a day before the [[People's Climate March (2014)|People's Climate March]], Hedges joined [[Bernie Sanders]], [[Naomi Klein]], [[Bill McKibben]], and [[Kshama Sawant]] on a panel moderated by WNYC's [[Brian Lehrer]] to discuss the issue of climate change.<ref>[http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=74&jumival=12411&updaterx=2014-09-21+13%3A06%3A09 \"It's Time to Act on the Climate Crisis\"]. The Real News, September 21, 2014</ref> Hedges and Klein also participated in the 'Flood Wall Street' protests that occurred shortly thereafter.<ref>{{cite news |author=John Light |author2=Joshua Holland |url=http://billmoyers.com/2014/09/23/flood-wall-street/ |title=After People's Climate March, Thousands Re-Kindle Occupy Wall Street |publisher=[[Moyers & Company]] |date=September 23, 2014 |accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn November 11, 2014, Hedges published an article explaining why he and his family have become [[Veganism|vegan]]. He explained that this is \"the most important and direct change we can immediately make to save the planet and its species\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/saving_the_planet_one_meal_at_a_time_20141109|title=Saving the Planet, One Meal at a Time|publisher=Truthdig|date=November 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a December 15, 2014, article, Hedges compared the actions of [[Islamic State of Iraq and Syria|ISIS]] today to the way [[Israel]]'s founding fathers acted in the late 1940s.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hedges|first1=Chris|title=ISIS-The New Israel|url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/isis_--_the_new_israel_20141214|website=TruthDig}}</ref>\n\nHe contended at the Left Forum in 2015 that with the \"denouement of capitalism and the disintegration of globalism\", [[Karl Marx]] has been \"vindicated as capitalism's most prescient and important critic\". He said that Marx \"foresaw that capitalism had built within it the seeds of its own destruction. He knew that reigning ideologies\u2014think [[neoliberalism]]\u2014were created to serve the interests of the elites and in particular the economic elites.\"<ref>Chris Hedges (May 31, 2015). [http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/karl_marx_was_right_20150531 Karl Marx Was Right]. ''Truthdig.'' Retrieved June 5, 2015.</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2016, Hedges was arrested, along with 100 other protesters, during a sit-in outside the U.S. Capitol during [[Democracy Spring]] to protest the capture of the political system by corporations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dcmediagroup.us/2016/04/15/rosario-dawson-arrested-100-democracy-spring-protesters-u-s-capitol|title=Rosario Dawson Among 100 Democracy Spring Protesters Arrested at U.S. Capitol|publisher=DCMediaGroup|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCommenting on the 2016 election during an interview on [[The Real News]], Hedges asserted that the modern American Left's embrace of neoliberalism resulted in a dysfunctional democracy and has given rise to a Trump presidency, which he characterizes as \"[[Proto-fascism|proto-fascist]]\".<ref>[http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=74&jumival=17650 Chris Hedges: The Surrender of the Liberal Left to Neoliberalism Gave Us Proto-fascism]. ''[[The Real News]].'' November 10, 2016.</ref> Hedges argues that logical result of neoliberalism is neofascism.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.truthdig.com/articles/neoliberalisms-dark-path-to-fascism/|title=Neoliberalism's Dark Path to Fascism|last=Hedges |first=Chris|date=November 26, 2018|website=Truthdig |publisher= |access-date=November 26, 2018 |quote=}}</ref> At a March 2017 speech delivered in [[Vancouver, British Columbia]], Hedges insisted that resistance to the Trump Administration must be broadly socialist and anti-capitalist in nature:\n<blockquote>This resistance must also be accompanied by an alternative vision of a socialist, anti-capitalist society. Because the enemy in the end is not Trump or [[Steve Bannon|Bannon]]\u2014it is corporate power. And if we do not stop corporate power, we will never dismantle fascism's seduction of the white working class and unemployed.\"<ref>[http://www.truthdig.com/avbooth/item/chris_hedges_enemy_donald_trump_or_steve_bannon_corporate_power_20170315 Chris Hedges: The Enemy Is Not Donald Trump or Steve Bannon\u2014It Is Corporate Power (Video)] Truthdig. March 15, 2017</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Plagiarism==\nHedges was caught plagiarizing multiple times over many years for his articles and books. At ''Harper\u2019s Magazine'', Hedges tried to lift material from Matt Katz before their Editor in Chief and publisher stepped in. At the time, Hedges told the fact checker that Katz approved of the manuscript where he lifted Katz work, only to find out later that Katz had never actually seen the draft.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"The Troubling Case of Chris Hedges\" |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/118114/chris-hedges-pulitzer-winner-lefty-hero-plagiarist |website=The New Republic |publisher=The New Republic |accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> Ross, the fact checker also said that the Hedges manuscript \u201ccould not have been anything but intentional. Specific language, specific sentence structure, specific topics. He went to all the same places as this reporter [Matt Katz], and talked to the same people. Some of it was just taken from the reporter\u2019s articles. There were sentences that were exactly the same.\u201d He elaborated \u201cHedges not only used another journalist\u2019s quotes but he used them in first-person scenes, claiming he himself gathered the quotes. It was one of the worst things I\u2019d ever seen as a fact-checker at the magazine.\u201d At the time of being caught, Hedges tried to go around the ''Harper\u2019s Magazine'' editor, Theodore Ross, by appealing to ''Harper\u2019s'' publisher Rick MacArthur who was his friend at the time. \n\n'''War is the Force That Gives us Meaning'''\n\nIn his most famous book ''War is the Force that Gives us Meaning'', parts were found out to be directly lifted from Hemingway\u2019s ''A Farewell to Arms''. There is no citation of Hemingway in Hedges' text, endnotes or bibliography. University of Texas classics professor Thomas Palaima, who caught the lift of words and ideas, said that when talking to Hedges about the lift he had  \u201cnever encountered a case where an unattributed use of another intellectual\u2019s ideas and wording was solved by altering the wording in a subsequent printing without attribution.\u201d\nOnce the plagiarism was discovered Hedges claimed that it was too costly for the publisher to add the Hemingway credit because text would have to be repaginated. \n\nHedges has also been caught lifting passages from Petra Bartosiewicz, a writer for ''Harper\u2019s Magazine''. In his article, he refers to Bartosiewic\u2019s article but doesn\u2019t explain that he had copied an entire paragraphs of hers. Hedges claimed that it was not formatted to show he correctly quoted her. Hedges never explained why he made small changes to the text if it was a block quote such as changing phrases of \u201cmy local reporter\u201d to \u201ca local reporter\u201d. \n\nIn his columns, Hedges lifted language and ideas from Neil Postman\u2019s \u201cAmusing Ourselves to Death\u201d but failed to include a citation. \n\n==NDAA lawsuit==\n{{Main|Hedges v. Obama}}\n\nIn 2012, after the Obama Administration signed the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2012|National Defense Authorization Act]], or NDAA, Hedges sued members of the U.S. government, asserting that section 2021 of the law unconstitutionally allowed presidential authority for indefinite detention without ''[[habeas corpus]]''. He was later joined in the suit, ''[[Hedges v. Obama]]'', by activists including [[Noam Chomsky]] and [[Daniel Ellsberg]]. In May 2012 Judge [[Katherine B. Forrest]] of the Southern District of New York ruled that the counter-terrorism provision of the NDAA is unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kuipers|first=Dean|title=Federal judge blocks National Defense Authorization Act provision |url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/environment/la-me-gs-national-defense-authorization-ruling-20120518,0,2046039.story|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=May 18, 2012}}</ref> The Obama administration appealed the decision and it was overturned. Hedges petitioned the U.S. Supreme Court to hear the case,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/unbelievable-obama-administration-has-already-appealed-ndaa-ruling-2012-9 | title =Obama Has Already Appealed The Indefinite Detention Ruling | author =David Seaman | website =Business Insider | date =September 13, 2012}}</ref> but the Supreme Court denied [[certiorari]] in April 2014.<ref name=\"SCOTUSblog20140428\">{{cite web |last=Denniston|first=Lyle|title=Detention challenge denied|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2014/04/detention-challenge-denied/|publisher=SCOTUSblog|accessdate=April 29, 2014|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"USC20140428\">{{cite web |title=Order List: 572 U. S. 13-758 Hedges, Christopher, et Al. V. Obama, Pres. Of U.S., et Al. \u2013 Certiorari Denied|publisher=United States Supreme Court|accessdate=April 29, 2014|page=7|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/042814zor_6k47.pdf|date=April 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Ordination and ministerial installation==\nOn October 5, 2014, Hedges was ordained a [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]] within the [[Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.)|Presbyterian Church]]. He was installed as Associate Pastor and Minister of Social Witness and Prison Ministry at the Second Presbyterian Church Elizabeth in [[Elizabeth, New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.secpreseliz.org/leadership|title=Leadership of the Second Presbyterian Church in Elizabeth, NJ |publisher= |date= |accessdate=April 27, 2015}}</ref> He noted having been rejected for ordination 30 years earlier, saying that \"going to [[El Salvador]] as a reporter was not something the Presbyterian Church at the time recognized as a valid ministry, and a committee rejected my 'call{{'\"}}.<ref name=\"Ordained to Write\">{{cite web |url=https://www.truthdig.com/report/item/ordained_to_write_20141013|title=Ordained to Write|publisher=Truthdig|date=October 13, 2014|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHedges is married to the Canadian actress Eunice Wong.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.eunicewong.com/biography |title= Eunice Wong: Biography |accessdate= May 14, 2016}}</ref> The couple have two children. Hedges also has two children from a previous marriage. He currently lives in Princeton, New Jersey.<ref name=\"TruthOrg\">{{cite web |url=http://www.americanswhotellthetruth.org/portraits/chris-hedges |title=Americans Who Tell the Truth.org \"Chris Hedges Biography\" |publisher=Robert Shetterly |accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* 2002: ''[[War Is a Force That Gives Us Meaning]]'' ({{ISBN|1586480499}})\n* 2003: ''What Every Person Should Know About War'' ({{ISBN|1417721049}})\n* 2005: ''Losing Moses on the Freeway: The 10 Commandments in America'' ({{ISBN|0743255135}})\n* 2007: ''[[American Fascists|American Fascists: The Christian Right and the War on America]]'' ({{ISBN|0743284437}})\n* 2008: ''I Don't Believe in Atheists'' ({{ISBN|141656795X}})\n* 2008: ''Collateral Damage: America's War Against Iraqi Civilians'', with [[Laila Al-Arian]] ({{ISBN|1568583737}})\n* 2009: ''When Atheism Becomes Religion: America's New Fundamentalists'', ({{ISBN|9781416570783}}), a retitled edition of ''I Don't Believe in Atheists''\n* 2009: ''Empire of Illusion: The End of Literacy and the Triumph of Spectacle'' ({{ISBN|9781568584379}})\n* 2010: ''[[Death of the Liberal Class]]'' ({{ISBN|9781568586441}})\n* 2010: ''The World As It Is: Dispatches on the Myth of Human Progress'' ({{ISBN|9781568586403}})\n* 2012: ''[[Days of Destruction, Days of Revolt]]'', with [[Joe Sacco]] ({{ISBN|9781568586434}})\n* 2015: ''Wages of Rebellion: The Moral Imperative of Revolt'' ({{ISBN|1568589662}})\n* 2016: ''Unspeakable'' ({{ISBN|1510712739}})\n* 2018: ''America, The Farewell Tour'' ({{ISBN|978-1501152672}})\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Hedges v. Obama]]''\n* {{section link|Tomas Young|The Last Letter}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{external media\n| align = right\n| width = 220px\n| video1 = {{YouTube|Q2klcRVZs0g|Stop Fascism: Chris Hedges in Portland, Oregon. A KBOO Benefit.}}\n| video2 = {{YouTube|0YdBzwJCpo8|On Contact: Noam Chomsky \u2013 Part I}}\n| video3 = {{YouTube|FaERQWrWLO0|Organizing resistance to Internet censorship}}\n| video4 = {{YouTube|6H07ygGZxjE&t|Chris Hedges talking about his book America: The Farewell Tour on MSNBC}}}}\n\n* [http://www.apbspeakers.com/speaker/chris-hedges APB Speakers Bureau Chris Hedges]\n* {{C-SPAN|Chris Hedges}}\n** [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/ChrisHed In Depth with Chris Hedges]. [[C-SPAN]]. January 1, 2012.\n* {{Charlie Rose view|2113}}\n* [http://billmoyers.com/episode/full-show-capitalism%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%98sacrifice-zones%E2%80%99/ \"Capitalism's 'Sacrifice Zones{{'\"}}] [[Bill Moyers]] talks with Chris Hedges, and comic-journalist [[Joe Sacco]] talking about their collaboration and showing drawings for their book ''Days of Destruction, Days of Revolt'', July 20, 2012. Retrieved July 30, 2012\n* {{cite news |date=March 13, 2008 |title=I don't believe in atheists |author=Charly Wilder |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon.com]] |url=http://www.salon.com/2008/03/13/chris_hedges/ |accessdate=January 17, 2015}} Interview with Chris Hedges.\n* [http://www.truthdig.com/staff/chris_hedges Columns by Chris Hedges] at [[Truthdig]]\n* [http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/chris_hedges_jan_27_column_transcript_collapse_of_complex_societies_2014012 The Myth of Human Progress and the Collapse of Complex Societies]. Truthdig, '' January 26, 2014. (The audio and transcript of a speech that Chris Hedges gave in Santa Monica, Calif., on Oct. 13, 2013.)\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2003/07/06/books/chapters/0713-1st-hedges.html?pagewanted=1 ''What Every Person Should Know About War'', first chapter] at ''[[The New York Times]]''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hedges, Chris}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American anarchists]]\n[[Category:American socialists]]\n[[Category:American Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:American foreign policy writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American Presbyterians]]\n[[Category:American reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:American war correspondents]]\n[[Category:War correspondents of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:War correspondents of the Yugoslav Wars]]\n[[Category:Anti-capitalists]]\n[[Category:Anti-consumerists]]\n[[Category:Anti-corporate activists]]\n[[Category:American anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:Christian Science Monitor people]]\n[[Category:Christian anarchists]]\n[[Category:Colgate University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:Critics of atheism]]\n[[Category:Harvard Divinity School alumni]]\n[[Category:Nieman Fellows]]\n[[Category:People from Schoharie, New York]]\n[[Category:People from St. Johnsbury, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Presbyterian socialists]]\n[[Category:The Dallas Morning News people]]\n[[Category:The Nation (U.S. magazine) people]]\n[[Category:The New York Times writers]]\n[[Category:PEN Oakland/Josephine Miles Literary Award winners]]\n[[Category:Loomis Chaffee School alumni]]\n[[Category:RT people]]\n[[Category:Writers about religion and science]]\n", "text_old": "{{use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Chris Hedges\n|image         = Chris hedges blur.jpg\n|image_size    =\n|caption       = Hedges, {{abbr|c.|circa}} 2007\n|birth_name    = Christopher Lynn Hedges\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1956|9|18}}\n|birth_place   = [[St. Johnsbury, Vermont|St. Johnsbury]], [[Vermont]], U.S.\n|death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|death_place   =\n|residence     = [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]], [[New Jersey]], U.S.\n|citizenship   = [[United States]]\n|ethnicity     =\n|education     = [[Colgate University]] <small>([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])</small><br />[[Harvard Divinity School]] <small>([[Master of Divinity|M.Div]])</small>\n|occupation    = Journalist, writer, activist, clergyman\n|employer      =\n|known_for     =\n|spouse        =\n}}\n'''Christopher Lynn Hedges''' (born September 18, 1956) is an American journalist, [[Presbyterian Church|Presbyterian]] minister, and visiting [[Princeton University]] lecturer. His books include ''[[War Is a Force That Gives Us Meaning]]'' (2002), a finalist for the [[National Book Critics Circle Award for Nonfiction]]; ''Empire of Illusion: The End of Literacy and the Triumph of Spectacle'' (2009); ''[[Death of the Liberal Class]]'' (2010); ''[[Days of Destruction, Days of Revolt]]'' (2012), written with cartoonist [[Joe Sacco]], which was a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' best-seller; ''Wages of Rebellion: The Moral Imperative of Revolt'' (2015); and his most recent ''America:  The Farewell Tour'' (2018).\n\nHedges was a columnist for the progressive news and commentary website [[Truthdig]].<ref>[http://www.truthdig.com/about Truthdig: About Us]</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=August 19, 2011 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/19/idUS428147016120110819 |title=Reuters Ex-LA Times Writer Mark Heisler Vents Again About Tribune |work=Reuters |accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2020/03/27/statement-from-striking-truthdig-workers/|title=Statement From Striking Truthdig Workers|date=2020-03-27|website=CounterPunch.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> He hosts the program ''On Contact'' for the [[RT (TV network)|RT]] (formerly Russia Today) television network.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ryan|first=Danielle|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/rt-america-was-not-pro-trump/|title=RT America Was Not 'Pro-Trump'|work=The Nation|date=January 10, 2017|access-date=August 4, 2019}}</ref> Hedges spent nearly two decades as a foreign correspondent in [[Central America]], [[Western Asia|West Asia]], [[Africa]], the Middle East, and the [[Balkans]]. He has reported from more than fifty countries, and has worked for ''[[The Christian Science Monitor]]'', [[NPR]], ''[[Dallas Morning News]]'', and ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref name=\"Simon\">{{cite web |url=http://authors.simonandschuster.com/Chris-Hedges/21025518|title=Simon & Schuster, \"Authors: Chris Hedges\"|work=Simon & Schuster|accessdate=November 27, 2014}}</ref> where he was a foreign correspondent for fifteen years (1990\u20132005).\n\nIn 2001, Hedges contributed to ''The New York Times'' staff entry that received the 2002 [[Pulitzer Prize for Explanatory Reporting]] for the paper's coverage of global terrorism. He also received the [[Amnesty International]] Global Award for Human Rights Journalism in 2002.<ref name=\"Chrisbiotruthdig\">{{cite web |title = Chris Hedges, Columnist |publisher = Truthdig |url = https://www.truthdig.com/staff/chris_hedges#bio |accessdate = 2013-09-28 }}</ref> He has taught at [[Columbia University]], [[New York University]], the [[University of Toronto]] and [[Princeton University]], where he is a visiting lecturer in [[African American studies]].<ref name=\"Simon\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Visiting Journalism Professors Roster 1964\u20132015|url=http://humanities.princeton.edu/journalism/professors/past|accessdate=28 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531003156/http://humanities.princeton.edu/journalism/professors/past|archivedate=May 31, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Anshutz Distinguished Fellowship in American Studies |url=https://www.princeton.edu/ams/anschutz/ |accessdate=28 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425054658/http://www.princeton.edu/ams/anschutz/ |archivedate=April 25, 2016 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=In Conversation with Brian Steward: Pulitzer-Prize Winning Journalist Christopher Hedges|url=http://munkschool.utoronto.ca/csus/event/9717/print/|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHedges has taught college credit courses for several years in New Jersey prisons. He teaches a course through Princeton University in which the class is composed of half prisoners and half Princeton undergraduates.<ref name=\"Chrisbiotruthdig\"/> He has described himself as a [[socialist]]<ref name=socialist>{{cite web |last=Hedges|first=Chris |url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/20081229_why_i_am_a_socialist/|title=Why I Am a Socialist|publisher=Truthdig|date=December 29, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Hedges |first=Chris |date=August 21, 2018 |title=America: The Farewell Tour |url= |location= |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |page=303 |isbn=978-0-73527-596-6 |author-link= }}</ref> and more specifically as a [[Christian anarchism|Christian anarchist]],<ref>Chris Hedges Interviewed at NYSEC [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tZSjKVijpjE&t=57m3s Youtube] Assessed 12/15/2016</ref><ref>Chris Hedges on What it Takes to be a Rebel in Modern Times [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BUgaqJZLwOg&t=16m21s Youtube] Assessed 12/15/2016</ref> identifying with Catholic activist [[Dorothy Day]] in particular.<ref>Occupy Tactics \u2013 Violence and Legitimacy in the Occupy Movement and Beyond [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F_cyzgYLaK4&t=1h15m31s Youtube] Assessed 12/15/2016</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nChristopher Lynn Hedges was born in [[St. Johnsbury, Vermont]], the son of Thelma Louise (''n\u00e9e'' Prince) and the Rev. Thomas Havard Hedges, a [[Presbyterian]] minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princetonmagazine.com/wordpress/?p=1749 |title=Chris Hedges The News Is Not Good |author=Ellen Gilbert |publisher=Princeton Magazine |date=February 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423211814/http://www.princetonmagazine.com/wordpress/?p=1749 |archivedate=April 23, 2014 }}</ref><ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:KFBV-4CZ Chris Hedges in FamilySearch]</ref> He grew up in rural [[Schoharie County, New York]], southwest of Albany. He graduated in 1975 from the [[Loomis Chaffee School]], a private [[boarding school]] in [[Windsor, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.collegequarterly.ca/2012-vol15-num01-winter/doughty.html | title =I Don't Believe in Atheists | author =Chris Hedges |author2=Howard A. Doughty | publisher =collegequarterly.ca | year =2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.loomischaffee.org/page.cfm?p=3613 | title =Notable Alumni Humanitarianism and Public Service | publisher =loomischaffee.org | date =May 15, 2013}}</ref> He founded an underground newspaper at the school that was banned by the administration and resulted in his being put on probation.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.courant.com/2003-02-21/news/0302210468_1_chris-hedges-iraq-poison | title =Writer Shares War Stories | author =Johnny Mason | newspaper=Hartford Courant |accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHedges received his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in English from [[Colgate University]] in 1979. He received a [[Master of Divinity]] degree from [[Harvard Divinity School]] (where he studied under [[James Luther Adams]]) in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/week622/hedges.html |title=Interview: Chris Hedges |publisher=PBS |date=January 31, 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310151925/http://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/week622/hedges.html |archivedate=March 10, 2013 }}</ref> He studied [[Latin]] and [[Classical Greek]] at Harvard and speaks [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[French language|French]], and [[Spanish language|Spanish]] in addition to [[English language|English]].<ref name=\"Chrisbiotruthdig\"/>\n\n==''The New York Times''== \nHedges worked for 15 years as a foreign correspondent for ''[[The New York Times]]''. He was based in the Middle East for five years, serving for four of those years as the Middle East bureau chief. He covered the war in the former Yugoslavia as the Balkan bureau chief based in Sarajevo. He later covered [[Al Qaeda]] in Europe and the Middle East from Paris.\n\nThree of Hedges' articles were based upon the stories of Iraqi defectors, who had been furnished to Hedges by the Information Collection Program of the U.S.-funded [[Iraqi National Congress]].<ref>[http://www.commondreams.org/headlines04/0316-02.htm Jonathan S. Landay and Tish Wells, \"Global Misinformation Campaign was Used to Build Case for War\" ''Knight-Ridder'', March 16, 2004] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131117010917/http://www.commondreams.org/headlines04/0316-02.htm |date=November 17, 2013 }}</ref> The program promoted stories to major media outlets in order to orchestrate U.S. intervention in Iraq in the aftermath of the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 attacks]]. Most significant of his reports in this period was a November 8, 2001, front-page story about two former [[Saddam Hussein and al-Qaeda link allegations|Iraqi military commanders who claimed to have trained foreign mujahedeen]] how to hijack planes without using guns.<ref name='alternet'>{{cite news | url = http://www.alternet.org/story/19210/ahmed_chalabi's_list_of_suckers | first = Douglas | last = McCollam | title = Ahmed Chalabi's List of Suckers: Judith Miller is only one of the many reporters from almost every blue-blooded news outfit in America who were played by the Iraqi exile | date = July 12, 2004| work = [[Alternet]] | accessdate = 2013-11-22 | quote = Chris Hedges of ''The New York Times'' wrote a page-one piece headlined \"Defectors Cite Iraqi Training for Terrorism\".}}</ref> Hedges quoted a man whom he believed to be an Iraqi general: \"These Islamic radicals ... came from a variety of countries, including Saudi Arabia, Yemen, Algeria, Egypt, and Morocco. We were training these people to attack installations important to the United States\". The two defectors also asserted there was a secret compound in [[Salman Pak facility]] where a German scientist was producing biological weapons.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/08/international/middleeast/08IRAQ.html%20| first = Chris | last = Hedges | title = Defectors Cite Iraqi Training for Terrorism | date = November 8, 2001 | work = [[The New York Times]] | accessdate = 2013-11-17}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Jack Fairweather (writer)|Jack Fairweather]] in ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'': \"The impact of the article ... was immediate: Op-eds ran in major papers, and the story was taken to a wider audience through cable-TV talk shows.<ref name='heroes in error'>{{cite news| last = Fairweather | first = Jack| authorlink = Jack Fairweather (writer) | title = Heroes in Error | date = March\u2013April 2006 | url = https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2006/03/heroes-error | work = [[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]| accessdate = November 17, 2013 | quote = How a fake general, a pliant media, and a master manipulator helped lead the United States into war.}}</ref> When [[Condoleezza Rice]], then President [[George W. Bush]]'s national security adviser, was asked about the report at a press briefing, she said, 'I think it surprises no one that Saddam Hussein is engaged in all kinds of activities that are destabilizing.{{'\"}} As late as 2006, according to Fairweather in the same article, conservative magazines including ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'' and ''[[National Review]]'' continued to use this article to justify the invasion of Iraq.<ref name='heroes in error' />\n\nIt later was revealed that the story which Hedges reported was \"an elaborate scam\". The defector whom Hedges quoted, who had identified himself as Lt. General Jamal al-Ghurairy, was a former sergeant. The real Ghurairy had never left Iraq. Hedges said that he had taken on reporting this account at the request of [[Lowell Bergman]] of ''[[Frontline (U.S. TV program)|Frontline]]'', who wanted the defectors for his show but could not go to Beirut for the interview. The trip had been organized by [[Ahmed Chalabi]], whom Hedges considered to be unreliable. Hedges said he had done the piece as a favor to Bergman, explaining, \"There has to be a level of trust between reporters. We cover each other's sources when it's a good story because otherwise everyone would get hold of it.\" Hedges had relied on the U.S. embassy in Turkey for further confirmation of the man's identity.<ref name=\"heroes in error\"/>\n\nHedges wrote two more articles that year that were informed by Chalabi-coached defectors. The second one, claiming that Iraq still held 80 Kuwaitis captured in the 1991 Gulf War in a secret underground prison, was also found to be baseless.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commondreams.org/headlines04/0316-02.htm |author1=Jonathan S. Landay |author2=Tish Wells |work=[[Knight-Ridder]] |date=March 16, 2004 |title=Iraqi Exile Group Fed False Information to News Media \u2013 Global Misinformation Campaign was Used to Build Case for War |accessdate=December 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131117010917/http://www.commondreams.org/headlines04/0316-02.htm |archivedate=November 17, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Political views and activism==\n{{quote box|width=23em|The Democratic Party is as much to blame for Trump as the Republicans. It is a full partner in the perpetuation of our political system of legalized bribery, along with the deindustrialization of the country, austerity programs, social inequality, mass incarceration and the assault on basic civil liberties. It deregulates Wall Street. It prosecutes the endless and futile wars that are draining the federal budget. We must mount independent political movements and form our own parties to sweep the Democratic and Republican elites aside or be complicit in cementing into place a corporate tyranny. Sanders won\u2019t help us. He has made that clear. We must do it without him.|salign=right|source=\u2014Chris Hedges on the Democratic Party<ref name=hedges>{{cite web|last1=Hedges|first1=Chris|title=Capitalism|url=https://www.truthdig.com/articles/et-tu-bernie-3/|website=truthdig.com|accessdate=17 June 2018|archive-url=|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>}}\nHedges was an early critic of the [[Iraq War]]. In May 2003, he delivered a commencement address at [[Rockford University|Rockford College]] in Rockford, Illinois, saying: \"We are embarking on an occupation that, if history is any guide, will be as damaging to our souls as it will be to our prestige and power and security.\"<ref>{{YouTube|SAWMgYyAtHU|Footage of the speech}}; Rockford College, May 2003</ref> His speech was received with boos and his microphone was shut off three minutes after he began speaking.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.democracynow.org/2003/5/21/new_york_times_reporter_chris_hedges|title=New York Times Reporter, Chris Hedges was Booed off the Stage and had his Microphone Cut Twice as he Delivered a Graduation Speech on War and Empire at Rockford College in Illinois |publisher=[[Democracy Now!]] |date=May 21, 2014 |accessdate=November 24, 2014}}</ref>\n{{American socialism |People}}\n''The New York Times,'' his employer, criticized his statements and issued him a formal reprimand for \"public remarks that could undermine public trust in the paper's impartiality\".<ref name=\"dallas\">Hedges, Chris; [http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/religion/stories/DN-main_17rel.ART.State.Edition1.21b687c.html A Father's Gift], ''[[Dallas Morning News]]'', 17 June 2006, accessed December 21, 2010 {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Shortly after the incident, Hedges left ''The New York Times'' to become a senior fellow at [[The Nation Institute]], and a columnist at [[Truthdig]], in addition to writing books and teaching inmates at a New Jersey correctional institution.<ref name=\"dallas\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nationinstitute.org/fellows/1328/chris_hedges |title=The Nation Institute |access-date=April 1, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150601032127/http://www.nationinstitute.org/fellows/1328/chris_hedges/ |archive-date=June 1, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHedges has worked for a decade teaching in prisons in New Jersey, and he has become a fierce critic of [[Incarceration in the United States|mass incarceration in the United States]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Marshall \"Eddie\" Conway |author2=Chris Hedges |url=http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=74&jumival=12928 |title=How Prisons Rip Off and Exploit the Incarcerated (1/2) |publisher=The Real News |date=January 4, 2015 |accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>Chris Hedges (December 29, 2014). [http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/the_prison_state_of_america_20141228 The Prison State of America]. Truthdig. Retrieved January 6, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn the 2008 United States presidential campaign, Hedges was a speech writer for candidate [[Ralph Nader]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://progressive.org/chris_hedges_interview.html |author=David Barsamian |title=An Interview with Chris Hedges |date=August 2011 |work=The Progressive |accessdate=November 27, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141204135757/http://www.progressive.org/chris_hedges_interview.html |archivedate=December 4, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2008, Hedges published a book titled ''I Don't Believe in Atheists'', in which he expresses his belief that new atheism presents a danger that is similar to religious extremism.<ref>{{Cite book|title=I Don't Believe in Atheists|last=Hedges|first=Chris|publisher=Free Press|year=2008|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn his December 29, 2008, column for Truthdig, Hedges stated that \"[t]he inability to articulate a viable socialism has been our gravest mistake. It will ensure, if this does not soon change, a ruthless [[Inverted totalitarianism|totalitarian capitalism]]\".<ref name=socialist/> He elaborated upon this in a 2013 interview with The Real News, claiming that, \"the left has been destroyed, especially the [[Far-left politics|radical left]], quite consciously in the whole name of [[Anti-communism#United States|anti-communism]]\", and:\n{{quote|[W]e have allowed ourselves to embrace an ideology which, at its core, states that all governance is about maximizing corporate profit at the expense of the citizenry. For what do we have structures of government, for what do we have institutions of state, if not to hold up all the citizenry, and especially the most vulnerable?<ref>[http://www.truthdig.com/avbooth/item/chris_hedges_the_left_has_been_destroyed_20130722/?ln Chris Hedges: 'The Left Has Been Destroyed']. Truthdig, July 22, 2013.</ref>}}\n\nIn a March 2009 column, Hedges warned that [[Human overpopulation|human over-population]] and [[Holocene extinction|mass species extinction]] are serious problems, and that any measures to save the ecosystem will be futile unless we cut population growth, and noted that, \"As long as the Earth is viewed as the personal property of the human race, a belief embraced by everyone from born-again Christians to Marxists to free-market economists, we are destined to soon inhabit a biological wasteland.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.truthdig.com/articles/we-are-breeding-ourselves-to-extinction/|title=We Are Breeding Ourselves to Extinction|last=Hedges |first=Chris |date=March 9, 2009|website= Truthdig|publisher= |access-date= January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 8, 2009, Hedges identified as a \"radical Keynesian\" during his lecture at [[The New School]], entitled \"Empire of Illusion\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_EpeF1fcji0|title=Chris Hedges' Empire of Illusion {{!}} The New School|last=Hedges|first=Chris|date=December 16, 2009|website=[[YouTube]]|publisher=[[The New School]]|access-date=August 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2010, he was arrested outside the White House along with [[Daniel Ellsberg]] and more than 100 activists who were protesting the war in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.truthdig.com/avbooth/item/hope_is_action_hedges_ellsberg_arrested_at_white_house_protest_20101217 |title='Hope Is Action': Hedges and Ellsberg Arrested at White House Protest|publisher=Truthdig|date=2010-12-17|accessdate=2014-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rawstory.com/rs/2010/12/untitled-chris-hedges-interview/ | title=Exclusive: US empire could collapse at any time, Pulitzer winner tells Raw Story |website=[[The Raw Story]]|date=December 17, 2010|accessdate=2014-11-24}}</ref>\n\nHedges appeared as a guest on an October 2011 episode of the [[CBC News Network]]'s ''[[Lang and O'Leary Exchange]]'' to discuss his support for the [[Occupy Wall Street]] protests; co-host [[Kevin O'Leary]] criticized him, saying that he sounded \"like a left-wing nutbar\". Hedges said \"it will be the last time\" he appears on the show, and compared the CBC to [[Fox News]].<ref>James Crugnale (October 12, 2011). [http://www.mediaite.com/tv/journalist-chris-hedges-argues-with-cbcs-kevin-oleary-this-sounds-like-fox-news-and-i-don%E2%80%99t-go-on-fox-news/ Journalist Chris Hedges Argues With CBC's Kevin O'Leary: 'This Sounds Like Fox News And I Don't Go On Fox News!'], ''[[Mediaite]].'' Retrieved January 24, 2014.</ref> CBC's ombudsman found O'Leary's heated remarks to be a violation of the public broadcaster's journalistic standards.<ref>{{cite news |author=Cassandra Szklarski |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2011/10/14/oleary-nutbar-ombudsman_n_1011373.html |title=Kevin O'Leary 'Nutbar' Remark Violated Journalistic Standards: CBC Ombudsman]. |work=The Huffington Post Canada |date=October 14, 2011 |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2011, Hedges was arrested with others in New York as part of the [[Occupy Wall Street]] demonstration, during which the activists staged a \"people's hearing\"<ref>[http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/chris_hedges_arrested_in_front_of_goldman_sachs_20111103/ Chris Hedges Arrested in Front of Goldman Sachs]. Truthdig. November 3, 2011.</ref> on the activities of the investment bank [[Goldman Sachs]] and blocked the entrance to their corporate headquarters.<ref>{{cite news |author=Rich Schapiro |author2=Helen Kennedy |date=November 3, 2011 |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/a-dozen-occupy-wall-street-protesters-arrested-goldman-sachs-article-1.971807 |title=More than a dozen Occupy Wall Street protesters arrested outside Goldman Sachs, Reporter/Activist Chris Hedges among those charged] |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |location=New York |accessdate=2011-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|w9qPGzqpuYc|RTAmerica}}</ref> Hedges has appeared on the syndicated ''[[Democracy Now!]]'' television program; on ''[[Breaking the Set]]'' on [[RT (TV network)|RT]] (formerly known as Russia Today), and on CBC's ''[[George Stroumboulopoulos Tonight]]''.<ref>[http://www.democracynow.org/appearances/chris_hedges Shows featuring Chris Hedges]. ''[[Democracy Now!]]'' Retrieved January 30, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://rt.com/shows/breaking-set-summary/fight-keystone-socialism-us-960/ |title=Socialist in Seattle: Kshama Sawant's revolution, the indigenous fight against Keystone XL |publisher=[[RT (TV network)|RT]] |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"strombo\">{{cite news\n|url         = http://www.cbc.ca/strombo/guest-page/chris-hedges-1.html\n|year        = 2010\n|title       = Strombo, Chris Hedges, CBC Television\n|publisher   = [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]\n|accessdate  = 2010-11-08 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, Hedges publicly supported [[Jill Stein]], the candidate of the [[Green Party of the United States]], in the [[2012 United States presidential election]].<ref name=\"Why I'm Voting Green\">{{cite web |last=Hedges|first=Chris|title=Why I'm Voting Green |url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/why_im_voting_green_20121029/|publisher=Truthdig|accessdate=April 7, 2013}}</ref> On April 7, 2013, Hedges delivered the keynote address at the [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]] of [[New Jersey]] state convention.<ref name=\"Green Party to livestream Chris Hedges keynote at NJ GP annual meeting, Sun. 4/9\">{{cite web |title=Green Party to livestream Chris Hedges keynote at NJ GP annual meeting, Sun. 4/9|url=http://www.greenpartywatch.org/2013/04/04/green-party-to-livestream-chris-hedges-keynote-at-nj-gp-annual-meeting-sun-49/|publisher=greenpartywatch.org|accessdate=April 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|C8H0ty327o0|Chris Hedges Strategy for Radical Change at Green Party of New Jersey Convention}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, Hedges and numerous celebrities appeared in a video showing support for [[Chelsea Manning]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/06/celebrity-bradley-manning-video-93041.html#ixzz2WgfpNmys |title=Celeb video: 'I am Bradley Manning' \u2013 Patrick Gavin |publisher=Politico |date=2013-06-20 |accessdate=2014-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|id=UFFkcCh-pCc|title=I am Bradley Manning (full HD)}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20, 2014, a day before the [[People's Climate March (2014)|People's Climate March]], Hedges joined [[Bernie Sanders]], [[Naomi Klein]], [[Bill McKibben]], and [[Kshama Sawant]] on a panel moderated by WNYC's [[Brian Lehrer]] to discuss the issue of climate change.<ref>[http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=74&jumival=12411&updaterx=2014-09-21+13%3A06%3A09 \"It's Time to Act on the Climate Crisis\"]. The Real News, September 21, 2014</ref> Hedges and Klein also participated in the 'Flood Wall Street' protests that occurred shortly thereafter.<ref>{{cite news |author=John Light |author2=Joshua Holland |url=http://billmoyers.com/2014/09/23/flood-wall-street/ |title=After People's Climate March, Thousands Re-Kindle Occupy Wall Street |publisher=[[Moyers & Company]] |date=September 23, 2014 |accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn November 11, 2014, Hedges published an article explaining why he and his family have become [[Veganism|vegan]]. He explained that this is \"the most important and direct change we can immediately make to save the planet and its species\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/saving_the_planet_one_meal_at_a_time_20141109|title=Saving the Planet, One Meal at a Time|publisher=Truthdig|date=November 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a December 15, 2014, article, Hedges compared the actions of [[Islamic State of Iraq and Syria|ISIS]] today to the way [[Israel]]'s founding fathers acted in the late 1940s.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hedges|first1=Chris|title=ISIS-The New Israel|url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/isis_--_the_new_israel_20141214|website=TruthDig}}</ref>\n\nHe contended at the Left Forum in 2015 that with the \"denouement of capitalism and the disintegration of globalism\", [[Karl Marx]] has been \"vindicated as capitalism's most prescient and important critic\". He said that Marx \"foresaw that capitalism had built within it the seeds of its own destruction. He knew that reigning ideologies\u2014think [[neoliberalism]]\u2014were created to serve the interests of the elites and in particular the economic elites.\"<ref>Chris Hedges (May 31, 2015). [http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/karl_marx_was_right_20150531 Karl Marx Was Right]. ''Truthdig.'' Retrieved June 5, 2015.</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2016, Hedges was arrested, along with 100 other protesters, during a sit-in outside the U.S. Capitol during [[Democracy Spring]] to protest the capture of the political system by corporations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dcmediagroup.us/2016/04/15/rosario-dawson-arrested-100-democracy-spring-protesters-u-s-capitol|title=Rosario Dawson Among 100 Democracy Spring Protesters Arrested at U.S. Capitol|publisher=DCMediaGroup|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCommenting on the 2016 election during an interview on [[The Real News]], Hedges asserted that the modern American Left's embrace of neoliberalism resulted in a dysfunctional democracy and has given rise to a Trump presidency, which he characterizes as \"[[Proto-fascism|proto-fascist]]\".<ref>[http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=74&jumival=17650 Chris Hedges: The Surrender of the Liberal Left to Neoliberalism Gave Us Proto-fascism]. ''[[The Real News]].'' November 10, 2016.</ref> Hedges argues that logical result of neoliberalism is neofascism.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.truthdig.com/articles/neoliberalisms-dark-path-to-fascism/|title=Neoliberalism's Dark Path to Fascism|last=Hedges |first=Chris|date=November 26, 2018|website=Truthdig |publisher= |access-date=November 26, 2018 |quote=}}</ref> At a March 2017 speech delivered in [[Vancouver, British Columbia]], Hedges insisted that resistance to the Trump Administration must be broadly socialist and anti-capitalist in nature:\n<blockquote>This resistance must also be accompanied by an alternative vision of a socialist, anti-capitalist society. Because the enemy in the end is not Trump or [[Steve Bannon|Bannon]]\u2014it is corporate power. And if we do not stop corporate power, we will never dismantle fascism's seduction of the white working class and unemployed.\"<ref>[http://www.truthdig.com/avbooth/item/chris_hedges_enemy_donald_trump_or_steve_bannon_corporate_power_20170315 Chris Hedges: The Enemy Is Not Donald Trump or Steve Bannon\u2014It Is Corporate Power (Video)] Truthdig. March 15, 2017</ref></blockquote>\n\n==NDAA lawsuit==\n{{Main|Hedges v. Obama}}\n\nIn 2012, after the Obama Administration signed the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2012|National Defense Authorization Act]], or NDAA, Hedges sued members of the U.S. government, asserting that section 2021 of the law unconstitutionally allowed presidential authority for indefinite detention without ''[[habeas corpus]]''. He was later joined in the suit, ''[[Hedges v. Obama]]'', by activists including [[Noam Chomsky]] and [[Daniel Ellsberg]]. In May 2012 Judge [[Katherine B. Forrest]] of the Southern District of New York ruled that the counter-terrorism provision of the NDAA is unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kuipers|first=Dean|title=Federal judge blocks National Defense Authorization Act provision |url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/environment/la-me-gs-national-defense-authorization-ruling-20120518,0,2046039.story|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=May 18, 2012}}</ref> The Obama administration appealed the decision and it was overturned. Hedges petitioned the U.S. Supreme Court to hear the case,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/unbelievable-obama-administration-has-already-appealed-ndaa-ruling-2012-9 | title =Obama Has Already Appealed The Indefinite Detention Ruling | author =David Seaman | website =Business Insider | date =September 13, 2012}}</ref> but the Supreme Court denied [[certiorari]] in April 2014.<ref name=\"SCOTUSblog20140428\">{{cite web |last=Denniston|first=Lyle|title=Detention challenge denied|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2014/04/detention-challenge-denied/|publisher=SCOTUSblog|accessdate=April 29, 2014|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"USC20140428\">{{cite web |title=Order List: 572 U. S. 13-758 Hedges, Christopher, et Al. V. Obama, Pres. Of U.S., et Al. \u2013 Certiorari Denied|publisher=United States Supreme Court|accessdate=April 29, 2014|page=7|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/042814zor_6k47.pdf|date=April 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Ordination and ministerial installation==\nOn October 5, 2014, Hedges was ordained a [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]] within the [[Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.)|Presbyterian Church]]. He was installed as Associate Pastor and Minister of Social Witness and Prison Ministry at the Second Presbyterian Church Elizabeth in [[Elizabeth, New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.secpreseliz.org/leadership|title=Leadership of the Second Presbyterian Church in Elizabeth, NJ |publisher= |date= |accessdate=April 27, 2015}}</ref> He noted having been rejected for ordination 30 years earlier, saying that \"going to [[El Salvador]] as a reporter was not something the Presbyterian Church at the time recognized as a valid ministry, and a committee rejected my 'call{{'\"}}.<ref name=\"Ordained to Write\">{{cite web |url=https://www.truthdig.com/report/item/ordained_to_write_20141013|title=Ordained to Write|publisher=Truthdig|date=October 13, 2014|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHedges is married to the Canadian actress Eunice Wong.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.eunicewong.com/biography |title= Eunice Wong: Biography |accessdate= May 14, 2016}}</ref> The couple have two children. Hedges also has two children from a previous marriage. He currently lives in Princeton, New Jersey.<ref name=\"TruthOrg\">{{cite web |url=http://www.americanswhotellthetruth.org/portraits/chris-hedges |title=Americans Who Tell the Truth.org \"Chris Hedges Biography\" |publisher=Robert Shetterly |accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* 2002: ''[[War Is a Force That Gives Us Meaning]]'' ({{ISBN|1586480499}})\n* 2003: ''What Every Person Should Know About War'' ({{ISBN|1417721049}})\n* 2005: ''Losing Moses on the Freeway: The 10 Commandments in America'' ({{ISBN|0743255135}})\n* 2007: ''[[American Fascists|American Fascists: The Christian Right and the War on America]]'' ({{ISBN|0743284437}})\n* 2008: ''I Don't Believe in Atheists'' ({{ISBN|141656795X}})\n* 2008: ''Collateral Damage: America's War Against Iraqi Civilians'', with [[Laila Al-Arian]] ({{ISBN|1568583737}})\n* 2009: ''When Atheism Becomes Religion: America's New Fundamentalists'', ({{ISBN|9781416570783}}), a retitled edition of ''I Don't Believe in Atheists''\n* 2009: ''Empire of Illusion: The End of Literacy and the Triumph of Spectacle'' ({{ISBN|9781568584379}})\n* 2010: ''[[Death of the Liberal Class]]'' ({{ISBN|9781568586441}})\n* 2010: ''The World As It Is: Dispatches on the Myth of Human Progress'' ({{ISBN|9781568586403}})\n* 2012: ''[[Days of Destruction, Days of Revolt]]'', with [[Joe Sacco]] ({{ISBN|9781568586434}})\n* 2015: ''Wages of Rebellion: The Moral Imperative of Revolt'' ({{ISBN|1568589662}})\n* 2016: ''Unspeakable'' ({{ISBN|1510712739}})\n* 2018: ''America, The Farewell Tour'' ({{ISBN|978-1501152672}})\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Hedges v. Obama]]''\n* {{section link|Tomas Young|The Last Letter}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{external media\n| align = right\n| width = 220px\n| video1 = {{YouTube|Q2klcRVZs0g|Stop Fascism: Chris Hedges in Portland, Oregon. A KBOO Benefit.}}\n| video2 = {{YouTube|0YdBzwJCpo8|On Contact: Noam Chomsky \u2013 Part I}}\n| video3 = {{YouTube|FaERQWrWLO0|Organizing resistance to Internet censorship}}\n| video4 = {{YouTube|6H07ygGZxjE&t|Chris Hedges talking about his book America: The Farewell Tour on MSNBC}}}}\n\n* [http://www.apbspeakers.com/speaker/chris-hedges APB Speakers Bureau Chris Hedges]\n* {{C-SPAN|Chris Hedges}}\n** [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/ChrisHed In Depth with Chris Hedges]. [[C-SPAN]]. January 1, 2012.\n* {{Charlie Rose view|2113}}\n* [http://billmoyers.com/episode/full-show-capitalism%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%98sacrifice-zones%E2%80%99/ \"Capitalism's 'Sacrifice Zones{{'\"}}] [[Bill Moyers]] talks with Chris Hedges, and comic-journalist [[Joe Sacco]] talking about their collaboration and showing drawings for their book ''Days of Destruction, Days of Revolt'', July 20, 2012. Retrieved July 30, 2012\n* {{cite news |date=March 13, 2008 |title=I don't believe in atheists |author=Charly Wilder |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon.com]] |url=http://www.salon.com/2008/03/13/chris_hedges/ |accessdate=January 17, 2015}} Interview with Chris Hedges.\n* [http://www.truthdig.com/staff/chris_hedges Columns by Chris Hedges] at [[Truthdig]]\